Lokmat]]|season=3|last=Wagle |first=Nikhil(host)}}</ref> In relation to the control of malaria he is quoted to have said \"Show me one mosquito (in Hiware bazar) and take away Rs 100.\"<ref name=\"TS-20120129\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=398363&catid=52|title=Big talk, tall promises & zilch|last=Mukhim|first=Patricia|date=2012-01-29|work=The Statesman|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref>\nHe speaks regularly at Policy BootCamp <ref> https://visionindiafoundation.com/aboutus/team/</ref>, a flagship summer school in public policy conducted by [[Vision India Foundation]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pawar, Popatrao Baguji}}\n[[Category:Activists from Maharashtra]]\n[[Category:Maharashtra politicians]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Ahmednagar district]]\n\n\n{{India-activist-stub}}\n{{Maharashtra-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ziyush", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Padamshree Award details", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Popatrao_Baguji_Pawar"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Dee Richards", "text_new": "{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Stephen Dee Richards\n| image=StephenDeeRichards.jpg\n| caption= Illustration of Richards first published in the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]'' in 1879\n| alias= Samuel D. Richards,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Wilson|2014|p=11}} Stephen Lee Richards,{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}}{{sfn|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=317}} The Nebraska Fiend,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}} Kearney County Murderer\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1856|3|18}}\n| birth_place=[[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1879|4|26|1856|3|18}}\n| death_place=[[Minden, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| cause=Execution by [[hanging]]\n| victims=6-9\n| country=[[United States]]\n| states=[[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]]\n| apprehended=December 1878\n| penalty=Execution by [[hanging]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Dee Richards'''  (March 18, 1856 \u2013 April 26, 1879), also known in the media as the \"'''Nebraska Fiend,'''\" and the \"'''Kearney County Murderer'''\", was an American [[serial killer]] who confessed to committing six to nine murders in [[Nebraska]] and [[Iowa]] between 1876 and 1878. \n\nRichards was born in [[West Virginia]], though one source claimed that he was born in born in [[Ohio]], with his family moving around until settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. In 1876, Richards left his home in Mount Pleasant, heading Westward with the intention of 'seeking his fortune'. For a time, Richards found work at a local [[Sanatorium|asylum]], where he claimed to have lost all empathy towards others during his time there. In his later confessions, Richards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]]. After committing several other murders, in which he claimed was [[Murder in self defense|self-defense]], Richards later fled after the murder of the Harlson family, eventually being captured in his home town of Mount Pleasant. He was later tried and hanged in 1879, for the murder of Mrs. Harlson and her three children, and for the murder of his neighbor Peter Anderson.\n\nRichards later became known through an [[biography]], which was based on an interview conducted during his final arrest. The biography, which also included entries on other criminals of the time, was published [[posthumously]] in 1879, by the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]''. Richards was later featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', where his spirit was purported to have tormented a family.\n\n==Early and young adult life==\nStephen Dee Richards was born in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]],{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note1|group=Note|In a biography published shortly after his execution, its author claimed that Richards was born in Ohio.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}}} on March 18, 1856.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of six, Richards moved with his family out of state to [[Ohio]], first settling in [[Monroe County, Ohio|Monroe county]], before later moving on to [[Noble County, Ohio|Noble County]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of eleven, his family moved once again, settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. Richards later described his mother as being a devout [[Methodist]], while claiming his father, a farmer,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} \"made no profession of religion\". During his residency in Mount Pleasant, Richards attended school, where he claimed that teachers there considered him well-behaved. At his mother's insistence, he also attended [[Sunday school]] and church regularly.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} \n\nRichards would remain under his parents' roof during this time, working for farmers and other locals in the area. On September 16, 1871, Richards' mother passed away from unknown causes.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=11}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Several years later, the age of 20, Richards met and became engaged to a young woman named Anna Millhorne, whom he kept regular correspondence with during his later travels up until his final arrest.  Also during this time, Richards came in contact with men of questionable occupation, and began passing around [[Counterfeiting of money|counterfeit bills]] that he claimed, had obtained through a man in [[New York City|New York]]. In February 1876, Richards left Mount Pleasant, heading west to \"seek his fortune\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=12}}\n\nFor a time, Richards set up residency in [[Iowa]], where he worked around as a farmhand at various local farms in [[Burlington, Iowa|Burlington]] and [[Morning Sun, Iowa|Morning Sun]]. He was later hired as an attendant at the [[Mount Pleasant Mental Health Institute|Iowa Lunatic Asylum]] in [[Mount Pleasant, Iowa|Mount Pleasant]], where his job was to bury dead patients. The ''New York Times'' reported that Richards \"had his finer senses blunted\" during his time at the asylum.{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} In a quote in the ''Omaha Herald'', Richards reported claimed that his time working at the asylum made him lose much of his empathy for others:\n\"When I left there... I didn't care for anything and had no respect for human nature.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}\n\nBy fall of 1876, Richards had left his job at the asylum and began drifting around the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], finding intermittent work and occasionally consorting with [[Train robbery|train robbers]].{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Eventually, he passed through [[Kansas City]] and [[Hastings, Nebraska]] before arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}}\n\n==Murders==\n===Early murders===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Dobytown, Nebraska 3.jpg\n| width1    = 295\n| alt1      = A photograph of a historical marker for Dobytown, Nebraska\n| image2    = Nebraska Sandhills NE97 Hooker County 3.JPG\n| width2    = 260\n| alt2      = A photograph of a prairie roadside in Sand Hills, Nebraska\n| footer = Newspaper records at the time reported that Richards confessed to have commited his first murder near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]] (left), or near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]] (right).\n}}\n\nIn a confession written after his final arrest, Richards confessed to having killed four men in 1876 and 1877 during his travels around Nebraska and Iowa.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=10-11}}\n\nRichards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in Kearney. According to his account, Richards met another man while traveling on horseback through the Nebraska countryside, and the pair soon decided to camp out for the night near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]],{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}} though several newspaper records have alternately reported that Richards had camped near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]].{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  Settling down for the night, the two began gambling in a game of cards, with Richards winning most of the stranger's money. The following morning, as the two set off for Kearney, the stranger turned on Richards, demanding his money back. After refusing to return the man's money, Richards claimed that the man grew belligerent, resulting in Richards shooting him above the left eye, killing the man instantly. Confirming that the man was dead, Richards disposed of the body in the nearby river.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}\n\nSeveral days later, while continuing towards Kearney, Richards encountered another stranger who was traveling on foot. The man told Richards that he had seen him in company with the stranger he had killed several days earlier and asked what had become of him;{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}{{refn|name=Note2|group=Note|In his confession, Richards stated that the stranger had identified the murdered man as being named John, although he later admitted that he was unable to find out the man's last name.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}}} in the course of the conversation, he realized that the two men were friends and business partners. Although he denied any knowledge of the other man, the stranger continued to hound Richards with questions.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Growing increasingly nervous from the stranger's interrogatory questions, Richards decided to kill the man to stop him from talking. Richards later stated that he waited until the stranger's back was turned, at which point he shot him in the back of the head, killing him. After disposing of the body, he later sold the stranger's horse in a nearby town before continuing on the road to Kearney. Before arriving at Kerney, Richards later stopped at the home of Jasper Harleson.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Jasper's wife Mary,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} whom Richards described as being a \"free talker\", had noticed that his shirt was stained with blood and had asked him if he had been in a fight. Not realizing this, Richards jokingly replied that it must have come from the men he murdered, which ended the conversation.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}\nTraveling to [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], Richards used [[counterfeit money]] to purchase a horse and buggy from an unnamed man. Once Richards had left, the man soon discovered that the cash was counterfeit and tracked Richards down, demanding either good money or the return of his horse and buggy.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}} Richards initially refused, whereupon the man threatened to have him arrested. In response, Richards shot the man, burying his corpse before leaving the area.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=16}}\n\nIn March 1877, Richards left [[Grand Island, Nebraska]], on horseback with a young man with the last name of Gemge, heading to Kearney. Near the end of their journey, they camped for the night along the [[Platte River]] between [[Lowell, Nebraska|Lowell]] and Kearney. Richards woke at around 3 a.m. and aroused his partner, telling him that it was almost morning and that they ought to get back on the road; Gemge, infuriated at being woken so early, began arguing with Richards about the time. Richards tried explaining to Gemge that it was in fact 3 a.m., at which point Gemge began insulting him.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=17}} Richards later recounted what followed:\n\n{{Quote|text='It's a good thing you don't mean all you say,' I said. 'But I do mean it,\" he said. \"You don't want to mean it,' I said; and he picked up his revolver and saying, 'Here is something that backs all that I say,' cocked it. I looked at him, and thought, 'The fool acts as if he means to shoot,' and skipping out my little 33 I plugged him one in the head. That was the first trouble we had ever had.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}}}\n\n===Murders of the Harlson family===\n[[File:Harlson Family Murders, Nebraska State Journal, December 1878.jpg|thumb|A newspaper clipping from 1878 reporting the Harlson Family murders.]]\nIn June 1878, while in Kearney, Richards was arrested and jailed for larceny, which he later claimed was a \"false charge\". During his time in jail, he reunited with Mary Harlson, (In the transcription of Richards' confession, the name is spelled \"Harlson\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}} Other sources give alternate spellings, including \"Harrison\",{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} \"Harleson\",{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} \"Haralson\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} and \"Harrelson\"{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}). Jasper and another prisoner named Underwood had previously escaped from the Kearney jail, shortly before Richards\u2019 arrival. Mrs. Harlson had been jailed as well, on suspicion of aiding her husband during his escape.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Richards and Mrs. Harlson agreed that she would sell him the deed to her property for $600, six months later.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}\n\nAfter Richards was released from jail, he traveled around Nebraska for several months, doing business in Hastings, Bloomington and Grand Island, before arriving at the Harlson's Kearney County homestead on October 18, 1878. When Richards arrived, Mrs. Harlson transferred her property to him, and he settled down there for several weeks.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} It was later reported by the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' that Richards had married Mrs. Harlson on November 2nd, in what they alleged was a scam in order to acquire ownership of Harlson's land.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}  A month later, Richards decided to kill Mrs. Harlson and her three children: ten-year-old Daisy, four-year-old Mabel, and two-year-old Jasper, nicknamed \"Jesse.\" (Jasper Harlson was living in Texas at the time).{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} In his confession, Richards claimed that Mrs. Harlson 'talked too much', and had discovered that  he was guilty of murder: \"She would have 'given me away' had I let her live ... and so, knowing what she did, I thought it the safest plan to put her out of the way,\" he said.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}}\n\nOn November 3, 1878, Richards and another man named Brown, who had been staying at the house, got up early in the morning.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} Brown went to feed the horses and do other chores around the farm after Brown had left, Richards found a [[spade]] and dug a hole near the house, he then snuck back into the house and murdered Mrs. Harlson, Daisy, Mabel and Jesse with an [[Axe murder|axe]].{{refn|name=Note3|group=Note|According to one report, Mrs. Harlson, and one of the other children were murdered with a [[Steam iron|smoothing iron]], while the others were physically assaulted.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}}} In Richards' confession, most of the Harlsons died immediately after the first several blows, with the exception of Daisy, whom he claimed had 'writhed in pain for some time' before dying.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=21-22}} After the killings, Richards was said to have scrubbed away the bloodstains on the floor, and on his person, before sitting down for breakfast.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}} Afterward, he carried their bodies out of the house and buried them in the hole that he had made earlier. Later, when he was questioned about the Harlsons disappearance by several people, Richards claimed that they had left with Brown, and did not know when they would return.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} The bodies of Mrs. Harelson and her children were later discovered on December 11, with conflicting reports stating that they had been concealed underneath a haystack,{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}} rather than buried as Richards had later claimed.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}}\n\n===Murder of Peter Anderson===\nIn December 1878, Richards agreed to help his neighbor, a Swedish immigrant named Peter Anderson, with some work on Anderson's property.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} On December 9th,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}} Anderson became ill after eating a meal Richards had prepared, causing him to suspect Richards had poisoned him. Anderson told a neighbor of his suspicions, then confronted Richards, leading to a fight in which Richards beat Anderson to death with a hammer or hatchet.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=24}}{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Alternate newspaper accounts reported that Richards had shot Anderson.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later deny poisoning Anderson, saying using poison was not his style, and claimed that he killed in self-defense after Anderson attacked him with a knife.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Anderson's body was later discovered in the cellar of his house, buried underneath a pile of coal.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}\n\n==Fleeing the law==\nShortly after Anderson's murder, Richards decided to flee Kearny before the bodies would be discovered. However, a group of Anderson's neighbors approached Richards that evening in order to inquire about Anderson, whom they had not seen in a while. Arriving at the house, the group discovered Richards hitching up Anderson's horses, and when questioned about Anderson's whereabouts Richards reportedly distracted the group, claiming that Anderson was inside. As the neighbors entered the house, Richards fled the scene on horseback to [[Bloomington, Nebraska|Bloomington]].{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}\n\nFleeing the area, Richards traveled east, alternating between horse, train, and foot, passing through Omaha, Chicago, (an article from the ''[[Lincoln Journal Star]]'' alternately claimed that Richards, under the alias Samuel Richards, had instead fled to [[Red Cloud, Nebraska|Red Cloud]] after the murder through Hastings, Chicago).{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} While on the run, he met up with Jasper Harlson, the ex-husband of Mrs. Harlson, and Underwood, traveling with them through [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Bridgeport, Ohio]] before reaching his hometown of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]].{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Nebraska state Governor [[Silas Garber]] issued an arrest warrant for Richards on December 16, 1878, with the reward of $200 (about $5,173.56 in 2020) for his arrest and conviction.{{sfn|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}\n\n===Capture===\nThe circumstances and location of Richards' eventual arrest have varied somewhat, with some newspaper records around that time reporting that Richards was arrested shortly after his arrival in Mount Pleasant.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} ''[[The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer]]'' reported that, upon arriving in a town near Mount Pleasant, Richards was subsequently identified by an old acquaintance, who detained him with the help of a colleague.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Most records at the time have listed the date of Richards' arrest as being December 24, 1878.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Though one contemporary source has claimed that Richards was arrested in [[Austin, Texas]] in early 1879,{{sfn|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}  \n\nRichards himself would later claim to have nearly evaded capture in Ohio, stating that he had intended to travel back to Nebraska, as he reasoned it would have been the last place anyone would have bothered to look. Richards also reported a different story of the circumstances of his arrest. In his account, sometime after arriving in his hometown in Jefferson County, he had attended a [[Ballroom dance|ballroom dance]] with two unidentified women. While strolling just outside of town, with the women in attendance, he claimed to have spotted what appeared to be several officers approaching him. Wanting to fight his way out, Richards told his companions to head back to town to which they refused, and as the officers confronted them, Richards surrendered.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later state that, if the women had left, he would not have been arrested:{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}\n\n{{Quote|text=\"If I hadn't had the two girls with me, I guess the constable, McGrew, who arrested me, would have been a dead man - either of us would, for I'd have shot.\"}}\n\nAfter his arrest, Ohio authorities jailed him in [[Steubenville, Ohio|Steubenville]], where he wrote two articles for the local newspaper, confessing to a total of nine murders{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note4|group=Note|Some newspaper accounts have alternately reported that Richards had confessed to six murders, rather than nine.{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}}} over a period of three years.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Sheriff David Anderson of [[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo County]] and Sheriff Martin of [[Kearney County, Nebraska|Kearney County]],{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} (an alternate record listed both Anderson and a Simon C. Ayer as the arresting officers){{sfn|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}} who had pursued Richards all the way from Nebraska to Ohio, later returned with him to Nebraska.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} [[Leavenworth, Kansas]] newspaper ''The Workingman's Friend'' reported that the Chicago authorities received a portion of the $200 reward.{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  At the time of his arrest, authorities suspected that Richards was a member or leader of a gang of outlaws that plagued the state,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} a sentiment that was not shared by ''[[The Nebraska State Journal]]''.{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} Public outrage towards Richards near the areas where his crimes were committed were said to be so intense that both Anderson and Martin{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} feared that Richards would be [[Lynching|lynched]] by the outraged townsfolk. As a result, authorities came to the decision that Richards was not to be transferred into any of those areas.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} Shortly before his trial, Richards voiced his suspicions that he would be convicted and hanged for his crimes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} \n\n==Trial==\nRichards' trial began on January 16, 1879, in [[Minden, Nebraska]], with Judge Gaslin presiding over the court proceedings. With the charges of [[murder in the first degree]], Richards pled [[Not guilty plea|not guilty]], arguing  that Anderson's murder was in self-defense, and therefore justifiable.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} After two hours of deliberation,{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Richards was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death by hanging,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} with the date for his execution set for April 26th, later that year.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}\n\n===Execution===\nUpon his return to Nebraska, The ''Omaha Herald'' reported: \"Richards manifested supreme indifference to his lot, was perfectly willing to be brought direct to Kearney Junction and said he had as soon died one way as another.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}} Shortly after Richards' trial, Sheriff Martin announced that the execution would be open to the public, though he was afraid that the large crowd of onlookers would be roused to violence.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879a|p=4}} Stephen Dee Richards was hanged in Minden on April 26,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} 1879.{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=399}} A crowd of approximately 25,000 was said to be in attendance to witness the hanging, and, at precisely 1 pm, Richards was led to the gallows by Sheriff Martin and his deputy. In his final words, Richards launched into an impassioned defense for his actions, again claiming that Anderson's death was in self-defense, while also claiming that he had nothing to do with the murder of the Harlson family. Richards then stated that he \"had faith in Christ\", and pleaded with the crowd to sing with him the hymn ''[[Come Thou Fount of Every Blessing]]''. At precisely 1:17 pm, Richards was hanged from the gallows, with the attending reporter for the ''[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]'' stating that it took fifteen minutes for the criminal to die.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} \n\nAfterwards, his body was buried in a nearby grave,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} which was later dug up and his bones scattered in the streets of Kearney.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} In 1882, it was reported that ''Kearney County Gazette'' had obtained Richards' skull and had placed it on display,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} the current location of the skull remains unknown.\n\n==Pathology==\n{{Quote box|width= 40%|align=right|quote=\"I have killed nine persons, and I can't say I feel any worse for it.\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}|source = Richards, describing his lack of guilt over his crimes}}\n\nAt the time of Richards' killing spree and execution, [[criminal psychology]] and [[Criminal profiling|profiling]] had not yet become a recognized field of study, having first been utilized during the [[Jack the Ripper|Jack the Ripper murders]] in 1888, nine years after Richards' execution.{{sfn|Bonn|2017}} Richards was observed by many to have displayed a complete lack of remorse towards his crimes, after his arrest.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} An article in the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' reported of Richards' mood after his capture as being 'carefree and cheerful'.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} Members of the press that interviewed Richards after his arrest were struck by his calm and collected behavior.{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} During an interview with a reporter from the ''Wheeling Daily Intelligencer'', Richards himself stated that he knew that he would be executed for his crimes, but also stated that he was unafraid of death and was \"ready to meet it\".{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} When his death sentence was announced by the jury, Richards mood was said to have been cheerful after the verdict.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} In a report for the ''St. Louis Globe-Democrat'', who also expressed doubt over the number of murders Richards claimed to have committed, was said to have broken down during his final moments.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} \n\nConsidered reasonably handsome by observers, Richards was described by reporters at the time of his arrest as being \"heavily built\", standing approximately six feet tall, with dark hair and blue eyes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}\n\n==Legacy==\nBefore his execution in 1879, Richards was interviewed by the Nebraska [[State Journal]]. The interview was later published after Richards' execution on May 1, 1879, under the title ''Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards, the Murderer of Nine Persons Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1879''. The book would also include entries of other criminal cases at the time.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=72}}{{sfn|McDade|1961|p=239}} A detailed analysis of Richards' was later published by J. Sanderson Christianson titled ''The Philosophy of Insanity: Richard, the Nebraska Fiend''.{{sfn|Bell|1885|p=668}}\n\nRichards was also featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', in an episode titled \"The Nebraska Fiend\" where a family was reportedly tormented by the killer's [[spirit]].{{sfn|MTTG 2016}}{{snf|Enk|2016}}{{sfn|SyfyChannel|2016}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bell|first1=Clark|title=The Medico-Legal Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7RXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA668|volume=49|year=1885|publisher=Medico-Legal Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Jenkins|2004|p=39}}|author=Philip Jenkins|title=Moral Panic: Changing Concepts of the Child Molester in Modern America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_wT9QQgu1IC&pg=PA35|date=December 2004|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-10963-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McDade|first=Thomas|title=The annals of murder: a bibliography of books and pamphlets on American murders from colonial times to 1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98s-AAAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Newton|2006|p=117}}|author=Michael Newton|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA117|date=February 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}|editor=John Lewis|title=Messages and Proclamations of the Governors of Nebraska, 1854-1941|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HxpSAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501|volume=1|year=1942|publisher=Nebraska State Historical Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}|author=Katherine M. Ramsland|title=Inside the Minds of Serial Killers: Why They Kill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qbppiQQw4DkC&pg=PA4|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-99099-2}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1879b|pp=1-72}}|author=Anon.|title=Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards: The Murderer of Nine Persons, Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1878|year=May 1, 1879|publisher=State Journal Co.|location=Lincoln, Nebraska}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}}|author=Nebraska Senate Legislature|title=Senate Journal of the Legislature of the State of Nebraska: Fifteenth Regular Session|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5edKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA521|volume=15|year=1879|publisher=Journal Company, State Printers}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}|author1=Negley King Teeters|author2=Jack H. Hedblom|title=\"... Hang by the neck ...\": the legal use of scaffold and noose, gibbet, stake, and firing squad from colonial times to the present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fFNCAAAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=C. C. Thomas}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Wilson|2014|pp=11-13}}|author=R. Michael Wilson|title=Legal Executions in Nebraska, Kansas and Oklahoma Including the Indian Territory: A Comprehensive Registry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XEKou1ogxpoC&pg=PA11|date=January 10, 2014|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=978-0-7864-8909-1}}\n{{colend}}\n\n===Websites===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, the Kearney County Murderer, Gives for the First Time Full Details of His Crimes|newspaper=The [[Omaha Herald]]|date=December 31, 1878|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|OmahaHerald 1878}}}} \n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Watching for a Wholesale Murderer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37185412/stephen_dee_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Daily Herald|date=December 14, 1878|location=New York, New York|page=7|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=A Vile Murderer: A Prisoner Confesses to Having Murdered Nine Persons Over Three Years|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37226867/stephen_d_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 30, 2019|agency=The New York Daily Herald|date=December 25, 1878|location=New York, New York|page=5|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Steubenville Murderer Turns Out to be of Wheeling Origin|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488801/stephen-dee-richards-the-wheeling/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|agency=The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer|date=December 25, 1878|location=Wheeling, West Virginia|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Friday, December 27, 1878|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488992/stephen-d-richards-the-nebraska-state/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Nebraska State Journal|date=December 27, 1878|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, the Murderer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489307/stephen_d_richards_quadcity_times/|accessdate=January 30, 2020 |publisher=Quad-City Times|date=December 28, 1878|location=Davenport, Iowa|page=1|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=A Hardened Criminal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489122/stephen-d-richards-the-atchison-daily/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=The Atchison Daily Champion|date=December 29, 1878|location=Atchison, Kansas|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, The Mount Pleasant Criminal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489383/stephen-d-richards-belmont-chronicle/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Belmont Chronicle|date=January 2, 1879|location=Saint Clairsville, Ohio|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=State News and Notes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=3743132&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjczNjgxOTk3LCJpYXQiOjE1NjI4NjUwMDYsImV4cCI6MTU2Mjk1MTQwNn0.Of-5-JfeCnbQEy3AUugm7Tizt9sW9deCBs7Otnb2T00|accessdate=July 11, 2019|publisher=Nebraska Advertiser|date=January 23, 1879|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Nebraska Murderer: A Cool Confession of His Many Crimes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20590119/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 2, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Rande's Rival|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489246/stephen-d-richards-the-workingmans/|accessdate=April 7, 2020|publisher=The Workingman's Friend|date=January 3, 1879|location=[[Leavenworth, Kansas]]|page=1|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=He Killed Children as He Would Rabbits|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37184859/stephen_dee_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Daily Herald|date=January 7, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=7|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Nebraska Fiend|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32207600/stephen-dee-richards-is-the-nebraska/|accessdate=April 9, 2020|publisher=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=January 17, 1879|location=[[Sioux City, Iowa]]|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Scenes at a Hanging|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20358638/?terms=Stephen%2BRichards|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Times|date=April 27, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The City|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489162/stephen-d-richards-the-nebraska-state/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Nebraska State Journal|date=April 26, 1879|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|page=4|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1879a|p=4}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Craven Choked|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47865316/stephen-richards-st-louis/|accessdate=April 8, 2020|publisher=St. Louis Globe-Democrat|date=April 27, 1879|location=[[St. Louis, Missouri]]|page=4|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}}}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Bonn|first1=Scott|title=Criminal Profiling: The Original Mind Hunter|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/gb/blog/wicked-deeds/201712/criminal-profiling-the-original-mind-hunter|website=PsychologyToday.com|publisher=[[Psychology Today]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=December 4, 2017|ref={{sfnref|Bonn|2017}}}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Enk|first1=Bryan|title=Paranormal Witness News \u2013 Attend the Tale of Stephen Richards|url=https://www.syfy.com/paranormalwitness/blog/paranormal-witness-nebraska-fiend-stephen-richards|website=SyFy.com|publisher=Bryan Enk|accessdate=7 October 2019|date=14 September 2016|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|title=Nebraska's first legal executions|url=https://journalstar.com/nebraska-s-first-legal-executions/article_962c7ab2-7aa5-5e97-a635-129c58b58ba8.html|website=JournalStar.com {{subscription required}}|publisher=Lincoln Journal Star|accessdate=October 7, 2019|date=June 13, 2015|ref={{sfnref|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}}}\n*{{cite web|title='Paranormal Witness' 507 Nebraska Fiend aka Stephen Dee Richards visits|url=https://movietvtechgeeks.com/paranormal-witness-507-nebraska-fiend-aka-stephen-dee-richards-visits/|website=MovieTvTechGeeks.com|publisher=MTTG Staff|accessdate=October 7, 2019|date=September 15, 2016|ref={{sfnref|MTTG 2016}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=T.B. Murdock|title=Stephen D. Richards|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488635/stephen-d-richards-walnut-valley/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|publisher=Walnut Valley Times|date=April 27, 1879|location=[[El Dorado, Kansas]]|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|Murdock|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite web|title=Paranormal Witness Recap \u2013 Nebraska Fiend|url=https://www.syfy.com/paranormalwitness/episodes/season/5/episode/7/nebraska-fiend|website=SyFy.com|publisher=SyFy Channel|accessdate=April 8, 2020|date=September 14, 2016|ref={{sfnref|SyfyChannel|2016}}}}\n{{colend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Gordon Morris Bakken|title=Invitation to an Execution: A History of the Death Penalty in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pExe_keERQMC&pg=PT442|date=November 16, 2010|publisher=UNM Press|isbn=978-0-8263-4858-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bang|first=Roy|title=Heroes Without Medals: A Pioneer History of Kearney County, Nebraska|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q4wGAQAAIAAJ|year=1952|publisher=Warp Publishing Company}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ramsland|first=Katherine|title=The Human Predator: A Historical Chronicle of Serial Murder and Forensic Investigation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VtduoGffUgEC&pg=PT63|date=February 5, 2013|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-101-61905-6}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.R/r/richards-stephen.htm Stephen Richards on Murderpedia, the encyclopedia of murderers]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1879 deaths]]\n[[Category:1878 crimes]]\n[[Category:19th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Axe murder]]\n[[Category:Executed American serial killers]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:People executed by Nebraska by hanging]]\n[[Category:Murder in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox serial killer\n| name=Stephen Dee Richards\n| image=StephenDeeRichards.jpg\n| caption= Illustration of Richards first published in the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]'' in 1879\n| alias= Samuel D. Richards,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Wilson|2014|p=11}} Stephen Lee Richards,{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}}{{sfn|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=317}} The Nebraska Fiend,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|Jenkins|2004|p=35}} Kearney County Murderer\n| birth_date={{Birth date|1856|3|18}}\n| birth_place=[[Wheeling, West Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date={{Death date and age|1879|4|26|1856|3|18}}\n| death_place=[[Minden, Nebraska]], U.S.\n| cause=Execution by [[hanging]]\n| victims=6-9\n| country=[[United States]]\n| states=[[Iowa]], [[Nebraska]]\n| apprehended=December 1878\n| penalty=Execution by [[hanging]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen Dee Richards'''  (March 18, 1856 \u2013 April 26, 1879), also known in the media as the \"'''Nebraska Fiend,'''\" and the \"'''Kearney County Murderer'''\", was an American [[serial killer]] who confessed to committing six to nine murders in [[Nebraska]] and [[Iowa]] between 1876 and 1878. \n\nRichards was born in [[West Virginia]], though one source claimed that he was born in born in [[Ohio]], with his family moving around until settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. In 1876, Richards left his home in Mount Pleasant, heading Westward with the intention of 'seeking his fortune'. For a time, Richards found work at a local [[Sanatorium|asylum]], where he claimed to have lost all empathy towards others during his time there. In his later confessions, Richards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]]. After committing several other murders, in which he claimed was [[Murder in self defense|self-defense]], Richards later fled after the murder of the Harlson family, eventually being captured in his home town of Mount Pleasant. He was later tried and hanged in 1879, for the murder of Mrs. Harlson and her three children, and for the murder of his neighbor Peter Anderson.\n\nRichards later became known through an [[biography]], which was based on an interview conducted during his final arrest. The biography, which also included entries on other criminals of the time, was published [[posthumously]] in 1879, by the ''[[Nebraska State Journal]]''. Richards was later featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', where his spirit was purported to have tormented a family.\n\n==Early and young adult life==\nStephen Dee Richards was born in [[Wheeling, West Virginia]],{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note1|group=Note|In a biography published shortly after his execution, its author claimed that Richards was born in Ohio.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}}} on March 18, 1856.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of six, Richards moved with his family out of state to [[Ohio]], first settling in [[Monroe County, Ohio|Monroe county]], before later moving on to [[Noble County, Ohio|Noble County]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} At the age of eleven, his family moved once again, settling in the [[Quakers|Quaker]] village of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]. Richards later described his mother as being a devout [[Methodist]], while claiming his father, a farmer,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} \"made no profession of religion\". During his residency in Mount Pleasant, Richards attended school, where he claimed that teachers there considered him well-behaved. At his mother's insistence, he also attended [[Sunday school]] and church regularly.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} \n\nRichards would remain under his parents' roof during this time, working for farmers and other locals in the area. On September 16, 1871, Richards' mother passed away from unknown causes.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=11}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Several years later, the age of 20, Richards met and became engaged to a young woman named Anna Millhorne, whom he kept regular correspondence with during his later travels up until his final arrest.  Also during this time, Richards came in contact with men of questionable occupation, and began passing around [[Counterfeiting of money|counterfeit bills]] that he claimed, had obtained through a man in [[New York City|New York]]. In February 1876, Richards left Mount Pleasant, heading west to \"seek his fortune\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=12}}\n\nFor a time, Richards set up residency in [[Iowa]], where he worked around as a farmhand at various local farms in [[Burlington, Iowa|Burlington]] and [[Morning Sun, Iowa|Morning Sun]]. He was later hired as an attendant at the [[Mount Pleasant Mental Health Institute|Iowa Lunatic Asylum]] in [[Mount Pleasant, Iowa|Mount Pleasant]], where his job was to bury dead patients. The ''New York Times'' reported that Richards \"had his finer senses blunted\" during his time at the asylum.{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} In a quote in the ''Omaha Herald'', Richards reported claimed that his time working at the asylum made him lose much of his empathy for others:\n\"When I left there... I didn't care for anything and had no respect for human nature.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}\n\nBy fall of 1876, Richards had left his job at the asylum and began drifting around the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]], finding intermittent work and occasionally consorting with [[Train robbery|train robbers]].{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Eventually, he passed through [[Kansas City]] and [[Hastings, Nebraska]] before arriving in [[Kearney, Nebraska]].{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}}\n\n==Murders==\n===Early murders===\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = horizontal\n| image1    = Dobytown, Nebraska 3.jpg\n| width1    = 295\n| alt1      = A photograph of a historical marker for Dobytown, Nebraska\n| image2    = Nebraska Sandhills NE97 Hooker County 3.JPG\n| width2    = 260\n| alt2      = A photograph of a prairie roadside in Sand Hills, Nebraska\n| footer = Newspaper records at the time reported that Richards confessed to have commited his first murder near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]] (left), or near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]] (right).\n}}\n\nIn a confession written after his final arrest, Richards confessed to having killed four men in 1876 and 1877 during his travels around Nebraska and Iowa.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=10-11}}\n\nRichards claimed to have committed his first murder sometime in late 1876, two weeks after arriving in Kearney. According to his account, Richards met another man while traveling on horseback through the Nebraska countryside, and the pair soon decided to camp out for the night near [[Dobytown, Nebraska|Dobytown]],{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}} though several newspaper records have alternately reported that Richards had camped near [[Sandhills (Nebraska)|Sand Hills]].{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  Settling down for the night, the two began gambling in a game of cards, with Richards winning most of the stranger's money. The following morning, as the two set off for Kearney, the stranger turned on Richards, demanding his money back. After refusing to return the man's money, Richards claimed that the man grew belligerent, resulting in Richards shooting him above the left eye, killing the man instantly. Confirming that the man was dead, Richards disposed of the body in the nearby river.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}\n\nSeveral days later, while continuing towards Kearney, Richards encountered another stranger who was traveling on foot. The man told Richards that he had seen him in company with the stranger he had killed several days earlier and asked what had become of him;{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=13}}{{refn|name=Note2|group=Note|In his confession, Richards stated that the stranger had identified the murdered man as being named John, although he later admitted that he was unable to find out the man's last name.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}}} in the course of the conversation, he realized that the two men were friends and business partners. Although he denied any knowledge of the other man, the stranger continued to hound Richards with questions.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Growing increasingly nervous from the stranger's interrogatory questions, Richards decided to kill the man to stop him from talking. Richards later stated that he waited until the stranger's back was turned, at which point he shot him in the back of the head, killing him. After disposing of the body, he later sold the stranger's horse in a nearby town before continuing on the road to Kearney. Before arriving at Kerney, Richards later stopped at the home of Jasper Harleson.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}} Jasper's wife Mary,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} whom Richards described as being a \"free talker\", had noticed that his shirt was stained with blood and had asked him if he had been in a fight. Not realizing this, Richards jokingly replied that it must have come from the men he murdered, which ended the conversation.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=14}}\nTraveling to [[Cedar Rapids, Iowa]], Richards used [[counterfeit money]] to purchase a horse and buggy from an unnamed man. Once Richards had left, the man soon discovered that the cash was counterfeit and tracked Richards down, demanding either good money or the return of his horse and buggy.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=15}} Richards initially refused, whereupon the man threatened to have him arrested. In response, Richards shot the man, burying his corpse before leaving the area.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=16}}\n\nIn March 1877, Richards left [[Grand Island, Nebraska]], on horseback with a young man with the last name of Gemge, heading to Kearney. Near the end of their journey, they camped for the night along the [[Platte River]] between [[Lowell, Nebraska|Lowell]] and Kearney. Richards woke at around 3 a.m. and aroused his partner, telling him that it was almost morning and that they ought to get back on the road; Gemge, infuriated at being woken so early, began arguing with Richards about the time. Richards tried explaining to Gemge that it was in fact 3 a.m., at which point Gemge began insulting him.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=17}} Richards later recounted what followed:\n\n{{Quote|text='It's a good thing you don't mean all you say,' I said. 'But I do mean it,\" he said. \"You don't want to mean it,' I said; and he picked up his revolver and saying, 'Here is something that backs all that I say,' cocked it. I looked at him, and thought, 'The fool acts as if he means to shoot,' and skipping out my little 33 I plugged him one in the head. That was the first trouble we had ever had.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}}}\n\n===Murders of the Harlson family===\n[[File:Harlson Family Murders, Nebraska State Journal, December 1878.jpg|thumb|A newspaper clipping from 1878 reporting the Harlson Family murders.]]\nIn June 1878, while in Kearney, Richards was arrested and jailed for larceny, which he later claimed was a \"false charge\". During his time in jail, he reunited with Mary Harlson, (In the transcription of Richards' confession, the name is spelled \"Harlson\".{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}} Other sources give alternate spellings, including \"Harrison\",{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} \"Harleson\",{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} \"Haralson\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} and \"Harrelson\"{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}). Jasper and another prisoner named Underwood had previously escaped from the Kearney jail, shortly before Richards\u2019 arrival. Mrs. Harlson had been jailed as well, on suspicion of aiding her husband during his escape.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Richards and Mrs. Harlson agreed that she would sell him the deed to her property for $600, six months later.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=19}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}\n\nAfter Richards was released from jail, he traveled around Nebraska for several months, doing business in Hastings, Bloomington and Grand Island, before arriving at the Harlson's Kearney County homestead on October 18, 1878. When Richards arrived, Mrs. Harlson transferred her property to him, and he settled down there for several weeks.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} It was later reported by the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' that Richards had married Mrs. Harlson on November 2nd, in what they alleged was a scam in order to acquire ownership of Harlson's land.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}  A month later, Richards decided to kill Mrs. Harlson and her three children: ten-year-old Daisy, four-year-old Mabel, and two-year-old Jasper, nicknamed \"Jesse.\" (Jasper Harlson was living in Texas at the time).{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} In his confession, Richards claimed that Mrs. Harlson 'talked too much', and had discovered that  he was guilty of murder: \"She would have 'given me away' had I let her live ... and so, knowing what she did, I thought it the safest plan to put her out of the way,\" he said.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}}\n\nOn November 3, 1878, Richards and another man named Brown, who had been staying at the house, got up early in the morning.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=20}} Brown went to feed the horses and do other chores around the farm after Brown had left, Richards found a [[spade]] and dug a hole near the house, he then snuck back into the house and murdered Mrs. Harlson, Daisy, Mabel and Jesse with an [[Axe murder|axe]].{{refn|name=Note3|group=Note|According to one report, Mrs. Harlson, and one of the other children were murdered with a [[Steam iron|smoothing iron]], while the others were physically assaulted.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}}} In Richards' confession, most of the Harlsons died immediately after the first several blows, with the exception of Daisy, whom he claimed had 'writhed in pain for some time' before dying.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|pp=21-22}} After the killings, Richards was said to have scrubbed away the bloodstains on the floor, and on his person, before sitting down for breakfast.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}} Afterward, he carried their bodies out of the house and buried them in the hole that he had made earlier. Later, when he was questioned about the Harlsons disappearance by several people, Richards claimed that they had left with Brown, and did not know when they would return.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} The bodies of Mrs. Harelson and her children were later discovered on December 11, with conflicting reports stating that they had been concealed underneath a haystack,{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}} rather than buried as Richards had later claimed.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}}\n\n===Murder of Peter Anderson===\nIn December 1878, Richards agreed to help his neighbor, a Swedish immigrant named Peter Anderson, with some work on Anderson's property.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=23}} On December 9th,{{sfn|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}} Anderson became ill after eating a meal Richards had prepared, causing him to suspect Richards had poisoned him. Anderson told a neighbor of his suspicions, then confronted Richards, leading to a fight in which Richards beat Anderson to death with a hammer or hatchet.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=24}}{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Alternate newspaper accounts reported that Richards had shot Anderson.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later deny poisoning Anderson, saying using poison was not his style, and claimed that he killed in self-defense after Anderson attacked him with a knife.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Anderson's body was later discovered in the cellar of his house, buried underneath a pile of coal.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}\n\n==Fleeing the law==\nShortly after Anderson's murder, Richards decided to flee Kearny before the bodies would be discovered. However, a group of Anderson's neighbors approached Richards that evening in order to inquire about Anderson, whom they had not seen in a while. Arriving at the house, the group discovered Richards hitching up Anderson's horses, and when questioned about Anderson's whereabouts Richards reportedly distracted the group, claiming that Anderson was inside. As the neighbors entered the house, Richards fled the scene on horseback to [[Bloomington, Nebraska|Bloomington]].{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}\n\nFleeing the area, Richards traveled east, alternating between horse, train, and foot, passing through Omaha, Chicago, (an article from the ''[[Lincoln Journal Star]]'' alternately claimed that Richards, under the alias Samuel Richards, had instead fled to [[Red Cloud, Nebraska|Red Cloud]] after the murder through Hastings, Chicago).{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} While on the run, he met up with Jasper Harlson, the ex-husband of Mrs. Harlson, and Underwood, traveling with them through [[Wheeling, West Virginia]], and [[Bridgeport, Ohio]] before reaching his hometown of [[Mount Pleasant, Ohio]].{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} Nebraska state Governor [[Silas Garber]] issued an arrest warrant for Richards on December 16, 1878, with the reward of $200 (about $5,173.56 in 2020) for his arrest and conviction.{{sfn|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}\n\n===Capture===\nThe circumstances and location of Richards' eventual arrest have varied somewhat, with some newspaper records around that time reporting that Richards was arrested shortly after his arrival in Mount Pleasant.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} ''[[The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer]]'' reported that, upon arriving in a town near Mount Pleasant, Richards was subsequently identified by an old acquaintance, who detained him with the help of a colleague.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}} Most records at the time have listed the date of Richards' arrest as being December 24, 1878.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Though one contemporary source has claimed that Richards was arrested in [[Austin, Texas]] in early 1879,{{sfn|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}  \n\nRichards himself would later claim to have nearly evaded capture in Ohio, stating that he had intended to travel back to Nebraska, as he reasoned it would have been the last place anyone would have bothered to look. Richards also reported a different story of the circumstances of his arrest. In his account, sometime after arriving in his hometown in Jefferson County, he had attended a [[Ballroom dance|ballroom dance]] with two unidentified women. While strolling just outside of town, with the women in attendance, he claimed to have spotted what appeared to be several officers approaching him. Wanting to fight his way out, Richards told his companions to head back to town to which they refused, and as the officers confronted them, Richards surrendered.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} Richards would later state that, if the women had left, he would not have been arrested:{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}\n\n{{Quote|text=\"If I hadn't had the two girls with me, I guess the constable, McGrew, who arrested me, would have been a dead man - either of us would, for I'd have shot.\"}}\n\nAfter his arrest, Ohio authorities jailed him in [[Steubenville, Ohio|Steubenville]], where he wrote two articles for the local newspaper, confessing to a total of nine murders{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{refn|name=Note4|group=Note|Some newspaper accounts have alternately reported that Richards had confessed to six murders, rather than nine.{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}}} over a period of three years.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}} Sheriff David Anderson of [[Buffalo County, Nebraska|Buffalo County]] and Sheriff Martin of [[Kearney County, Nebraska|Kearney County]],{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} (an alternate record listed both Anderson and a Simon C. Ayer as the arresting officers){{sfn|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}} who had pursued Richards all the way from Nebraska to Ohio, later returned with him to Nebraska.{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}}{{sfn|NYTimes|1879|p=2}} [[Leavenworth, Kansas]] newspaper ''The Workingman's Friend'' reported that the Chicago authorities recieved a portion of the $200 reward.{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}  At the time of his arrest, authorities suspected that Richards was a member or leader of a gang of outlaws that plagued the state,{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} a sentiment that was not shared by ''[[The Nebraska State Journal]]''.{{sfn|StateJournal|1878|p=2}} Public outrage towards Richards near the areas where his crimes were committed were said to be so intense that both Anderson and Martin{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}} feared that Richards would be [[Lynching|lynched]] by the outraged townsfolk. As a result, authorities came to the decision that Richards was not to be transferred into any of those areas.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} Shortly before his trial, Richards voiced his suspicions that he would be convicted and hanged for his crimes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}} \n\n==Trial==\nRichards' trial began on January 16, 1879, in [[Minden, Nebraska]], with Judge Gaslin presiding over the court proceedings. With the charges of [[murder in the first degree]], Richards pled [[Not guilty plea|not guilty]], arguing  that Anderson's murder was in self-defense, and therefore justifiable.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} After two hours of deliberation,{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} Richards was found guilty of murder and sentenced to death by hanging,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} with the date for his execution set for April 26th, later that year.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}\n\n===Execution===\nUpon his return to Nebraska, The ''Omaha Herald'' reported: \"Richards manifested supreme indifference to his lot, was perfectly willing to be brought direct to Kearney Junction and said he had as soon died one way as another.\"{{sfn|OmahaHerald 1878}} Shortly after Richards' trial, Sheriff Martin announced that the execution would be open to the public, though he was afraid that the large crowd of onlookers would be roused to violence.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879a|p=4}} Stephen Dee Richards was hanged in Minden on April 26,{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} 1879.{{sfn|Newton|2006|p=399}} A crowd of approximately 25,000 was said to be in attendance to witness the hanging, and, at precisely 1 pm, Richards was led to the gallows by Sheriff Martin and his deputy. In his final words, Richards launched into an impassioned defense for his actions, again claiming that Anderson's death was in self-defense, while also claiming that he had nothing to do with the murder of the Harlson family. Richards then stated that he \"had faith in Christ\", and pleaded with the crowd to sing with him the hymn ''[[Come Thou Fount of Every Blessing]]''. At precisely 1:17 pm, Richards was hanged from the gallows, with the attending reporter for the ''[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]'' stating that it took fifteen minutes for the criminal to die.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} \n\nAfterwards, his body was buried in a nearby grave,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} which was later dug up and his bones scattered in the streets of Kearney.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} In 1882, it was reported that ''Kearney County Gazette'' had obtained Richards' skull and had placed it on display,{{sfn|LincolnJournalStar 2015}} the current location of the skull remains unknown.\n\n==Pathology==\n{{Quote box|width= 40%|align=right|quote=\"I have killed nine persons, and I can't say I feel any worse for it.\"{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}}|source = Richards, describing his lack of guilt over his crimes}}\n\nAt the time of Richards' killing spree and execution, [[criminal psychology]] and [[Criminal profiling|profiling]] had not yet become a recognized field of study, having first been utilized during the [[Jack the Ripper|Jack the Ripper murders]] in 1888, nine years after Richards' execution.{{sfn|Bonn|2017}} Richards was observed by many to have displayed a complete lack of remorse towards his crimes, after his arrest.{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=1}} An article in the ''[[New York Daily Herald]]'' reported of Richards' mood after his capture as being 'carefree and cheerful'.{{sfn|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}{{sfn|Murdock|1879|p=2}} Members of the press that interviewed Richards after his arrest were struck by his calm and collected behavior.{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}} During an interview with a reporter from the ''Wheeling Daily Intelligencer'', Richards himself stated that he knew that he would be executed for his crimes, but also stated that he was unafraid of death and was \"ready to meet it\".{{sfn|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=1}} When his death sentence was announced by the jury, Richards mood was said to have been cheerful after the verdict.{{sfn|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}} In a report for the ''St. Louis Globe-Democrat'', who also expressed doubt over the number of murders Richards claimed to have committed, was said to have broken down during his final moments.{{sfn|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}} \n\nConsidered reasonably handsome by observers, Richards was described by reporters at the time of his arrest as being \"heavily built\", standing approximately six feet tall, with dark hair and blue eyes.{{sfn|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}{{sfn|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}{{sfn|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}\n\n==Legacy==\nBefore his execution in 1879, Richards was interviewed by the Nebraska [[State Journal]]. The interview was later published after Richards' execution on May 1, 1879, under the title ''Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards, the Murderer of Nine Persons Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1879''. The book would also include entries of other criminal cases at the time.{{sfn|StateJournal|1879b|p=72}}{{sfn|McDade|1961|p=239}} A detailed analysis of Richards' was later published by J. Sanderson Christianson titled ''The Philosophy of Insanity: Richard, the Nebraska Fiend''.{{sfn|Bell|1885|p=668}}\n\nRichards was also featured in an episode of [[SyFy Channel]]'s ''[[Paranormal Witness]]'', in an episode titled \"The Nebraska Fiend\" where a family was reportedly tormented by the killer's [[spirit]].{{sfn|MTTG 2016}}{{snf|Enk|2016}}{{sfn|SyfyChannel|2016}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of serial killers in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n===Books===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Bell|first1=Clark|title=The Medico-Legal Journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T7RXAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA668|volume=49|year=1885|publisher=Medico-Legal Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Jenkins|2004|p=39}}|author=Philip Jenkins|title=Moral Panic: Changing Concepts of the Child Molester in Modern America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g_wT9QQgu1IC&pg=PA35|date=December 2004|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-10963-4}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McDade|first=Thomas|title=The annals of murder: a bibliography of books and pamphlets on American murders from colonial times to 1900|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98s-AAAAIAAJ|year=1961|publisher=University of Oklahoma Press}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Newton|2006|p=117}}|author=Michael Newton|title=The Encyclopedia of Serial Killers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DwNVbOcTncwC&pg=PA117|date=February 2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-0-8160-6987-3}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NSHistoricalSociety|1942|p=501}}|editor=John Lewis|title=Messages and Proclamations of the Governors of Nebraska, 1854-1941|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HxpSAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA501|volume=1|year=1942|publisher=Nebraska State Historical Society}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Ramsland|2006|p=4}}|author=Katherine M. Ramsland|title=Inside the Minds of Serial Killers: Why They Kill|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qbppiQQw4DkC&pg=PA4|year=2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-99099-2}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1879b|pp=1-72}}|author=Anon.|title=Life and Confession of Stephen Dee Richards: The Murderer of Nine Persons, Executed at Minden, Nebraska, April 26, 1878|year=May 1, 1879|publisher=State Journal Co.|location=Lincoln, Nebraska}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|NebraskaSenateJournal|1879|pp=501}}|author=Nebraska Senate Legislature|title=Senate Journal of the Legislature of the State of Nebraska: Fifteenth Regular Session|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5edKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA521|volume=15|year=1879|publisher=Journal Company, State Printers}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Hedblom|Teeters|1967|p=202}}|author1=Negley King Teeters|author2=Jack H. Hedblom|title=\"... Hang by the neck ...\": the legal use of scaffold and noose, gibbet, stake, and firing squad from colonial times to the present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fFNCAAAAIAAJ|year=1967|publisher=C. C. Thomas}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{sfnref|Wilson|2014|pp=11-13}}|author=R. Michael Wilson|title=Legal Executions in Nebraska, Kansas and Oklahoma Including the Indian Territory: A Comprehensive Registry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XEKou1ogxpoC&pg=PA11|date=January 10, 2014|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=978-0-7864-8909-1}}\n{{colend}}\n\n===Websites===\n{{refbegin|30em|indent=yes}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, the Kearney County Murderer, Gives for the First Time Full Details of His Crimes|newspaper=The [[Omaha Herald]]|date=December 31, 1878|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|OmahaHerald 1878}}}} \n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Watching for a Wholesale Murderer |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37185412/stephen_dee_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Daily Herald|date=December 14, 1878|location=New York, New York|page=7|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1878a|p=7}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=A Vile Murderer: A Prisoner Confesses to Having Murdered Nine Persons Over Three Years|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37226867/stephen_d_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 30, 2019|agency=The New York Daily Herald|date=December 25, 1878|location=New York, New York|page=5|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1878b|p=5}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Steubenville Murderer Turns Out to be of Wheeling Origin|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488801/stephen-dee-richards-the-wheeling/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|agency=The Wheeling Daily Intelligencer|date=December 25, 1878|location=Wheeling, West Virginia|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|WDailyIntelligencer|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Friday, December 27, 1878|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488992/stephen-d-richards-the-nebraska-state/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Nebraska State Journal|date=December 27, 1878|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, the Murderer|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489307/stephen_d_richards_quadcity_times/|accessdate=January 30, 2020 |publisher=Quad-City Times|date=December 28, 1878|location=Davenport, Iowa|page=1|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|QuadCityTimes|1878|p=1}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=A Hardened Criminal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489122/stephen-d-richards-the-atchison-daily/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=The Atchison Daily Champion|date=December 29, 1878|location=Atchison, Kansas|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|AtchisonDailyChampion|1878|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Richards, The Mount Pleasant Criminal|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489383/stephen-d-richards-belmont-chronicle/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Belmont Chronicle|date=January 2, 1879|location=Saint Clairsville, Ohio|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|BelmontChronicle|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=State News and Notes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=3743132&fcfToken=eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJmcmVlLXZpZXctaWQiOjczNjgxOTk3LCJpYXQiOjE1NjI4NjUwMDYsImV4cCI6MTU2Mjk1MTQwNn0.Of-5-JfeCnbQEy3AUugm7Tizt9sW9deCBs7Otnb2T00|accessdate=July 11, 2019|publisher=Nebraska Advertiser|date=January 23, 1879|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]] {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NebraskaAdvertiser|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Nebraska Murderer: A Cool Confession of His Many Crimes|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20590119/|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 2, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Rande's Rival|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489246/stephen-d-richards-the-workingmans/|accessdate=April 7, 2020|publisher=The Workingman's Friend|date=January 3, 1879|location=[[Leavenworth, Kansas]]|page=1|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|TheWorkingmansFriend|1879|p=1}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=He Killed Children as He Would Rabbits|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37184859/stephen_dee_richards_new_york_daily/|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Daily Herald|date=January 7, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=7|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYDailyHerald|1879|p=7}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Nebraska Fiend|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32207600/stephen-dee-richards-is-the-nebraska/|accessdate=April 9, 2020|publisher=[[Sioux City Journal]]|date=January 17, 1879|location=[[Sioux City, Iowa]]|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|SiousCityJournal|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=Scenes at a Hanging|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/20358638/?terms=Stephen%2BRichards|accessdate=October 15, 2019|publisher=New York Times|date=April 27, 1879|location=New York, New York|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|NYTimes|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The City|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37489162/stephen-d-richards-the-nebraska-state/|accessdate=April 6, 2020|publisher=Nebraska State Journal|date=April 26, 1879|location=Lincoln, Nebraska|page=4|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|StateJournal|1879a|p=4}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=Anon.|title=The Craven Choked|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/47865316/stephen-richards-st-louis/|accessdate=April 8, 2020|publisher=St. Louis Globe-Democrat|date=April 27, 1879|location=[[St. Louis, Missouri]]|page=4|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|GlobeDemocrat|1879|p=4}}}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Bonn|first1=Scott|title=Criminal Profiling: The Original Mind Hunter|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/gb/blog/wicked-deeds/201712/criminal-profiling-the-original-mind-hunter|website=PsychologyToday.com|publisher=[[Psychology Today]]|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=December 4, 2017|ref={{sfnref|Bonn|2017}}}}\n*{{cite web|last1=Enk|first1=Bryan|title=Paranormal Witness News \u2013 Attend the Tale of Stephen Richards|url=https://www.syfy.com/paranormalwitness/blog/paranormal-witness-nebraska-fiend-stephen-richards|website=SyFy.com|publisher=Bryan Enk|accessdate=7 October 2019|date=14 September 2016|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|title=Nebraska's first legal executions|url=https://journalstar.com/nebraska-s-first-legal-executions/article_962c7ab2-7aa5-5e97-a635-129c58b58ba8.html|website=JournalStar.com {{subscription required}}|publisher=Lincoln Journal Star|accessdate=October 7, 2019|date=June 13, 2015|ref={{sfnref|LincolnJournalStar 2015}}}}\n*{{cite web|title='Paranormal Witness' 507 Nebraska Fiend aka Stephen Dee Richards visits|url=https://movietvtechgeeks.com/paranormal-witness-507-nebraska-fiend-aka-stephen-dee-richards-visits/|website=MovieTvTechGeeks.com|publisher=MTTG Staff|accessdate=October 7, 2019|date=September 15, 2016|ref={{sfnref|MTTG 2016}}}}\n*{{cite news|author=T.B. Murdock|title=Stephen D. Richards|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/37488635/stephen-d-richards-walnut-valley/|accessdate=April 2, 2020|publisher=Walnut Valley Times|date=April 27, 1879|location=[[El Dorado, Kansas]]|page=2|via=Newspapers.com {{subscription required}}|ref={{sfnref|Murdock|1879|p=2}}}}\n*{{cite web|title=Paranormal Witness Recap \u2013 Nebraska Fiend|url=https://www.syfy.com/paranormalwitness/episodes/season/5/episode/7/nebraska-fiend|website=SyFy.com|publisher=SyFy Channel|accessdate=April 8, 2020|date=September 14, 2016|ref={{sfnref|SyfyChannel|2016}}}}\n{{colend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Gordon Morris Bakken|title=Invitation to an Execution: A History of the Death Penalty in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pExe_keERQMC&pg=PT442|date=November 16, 2010|publisher=UNM Press|isbn=978-0-8263-4858-6}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bang|first=Roy|title=Heroes Without Medals: A Pioneer History of Kearney County, Nebraska|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q4wGAQAAIAAJ|year=1952|publisher=Warp Publishing Company}}\n*{{cite book|last=Ramsland|first=Katherine|title=The Human Predator: A Historical Chronicle of Serial Murder and Forensic Investigation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VtduoGffUgEC&pg=PT63|date=February 5, 2013|publisher=Penguin Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-101-61905-6}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://murderpedia.org/male.R/r/richards-stephen.htm Stephen Richards on Murderpedia, the encyclopedia of murderers]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richards, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1854 births]]\n[[Category:1879 deaths]]\n[[Category:1878 crimes]]\n[[Category:19th-century American criminals]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of murder]]\n[[Category:American serial killers]]\n[[Category:American murderers of children]]\n[[Category:Axe murder]]\n[[Category:Executed American serial killers]]\n[[Category:Male serial killers]]\n[[Category:19th-century executions of American people]]\n[[Category:People executed by Nebraska by hanging]]\n[[Category:Murder in Nebraska]]\n[[Category:People from Wheeling, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Mount Pleasant, Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Orenburg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Dee_Richards"}
{"title_page": "List of government-owned companies", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{main|State-owned enterprises}}\nThis is a world-wide '''list of government-owned companies'''. This list can be considered as non-exhaustive because of lack of space and time. For example, China alone has in the [[wikipedia]] database as of October 2019 more than 350 individual entries in its \"Government-owned companies of China\" Category page.\n\nThe paragraph that follows was paraphrased from a 1996 [[GAO]] report which investigated only the 20th-century American experience. The GAO report did not consider the potential use in the international forum of SOEs as extensions of a nation's foreign policy utensils. A [[government-owned corporation]] is a legal entity that undertakes [[commerce|commercial]] activities on behalf of an owner [[government]]. Their legal status varies from being a part of government to [[joint-stock company|stock companies]] with a state as a regular [[shareholder|stockholder]]. There is no standard definition of a government-owned corporation (GOC) or state-owned enterprise (SOE), although the two terms can be used interchangeably. The defining characteristics are that they have a distinct legal form and that they are established to operate in commercial affairs. While they may also have public policy objectives, GOCs should be differentiated from other forms of government agencies or state entities established to pursue purely non-financial objectives.<ref name=gao>{{cite book|publisher=United States General Accounting Office|title=Report to the Ranking Minority Member, Subcommittee on Post Office and Civil Service, Committee on Governmental Affairs, U.S. Senate - GOVERNMENT CORPORATIONS - Profiles of Existing Government Corporations |pages=1\u201316|date=December 1995|quote=GAO/GGD-96-14|url=https://www.gao.gov/assets/230/222015.pdf}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Government-owned companies==\n\n=== Afghanistan ===\nIn 2009, the [[Government of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan]] formed the [[Afghan public protection force|Afghan Public Protection Force (APPF)]] as a \"state owned enterprise\" subordinate to the [[Ministry of the Interior (Afghanistan)|Ministry of the Interior]]. By presidential decree, the APPF is mandated to replace all non-diplomatic [[private security companies]] by 20 March 2013 to become the sole provider of pay-for-service security contracts within Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.appf.gov.af|title=Afghan Public Protection Force-\u0645\u0639\u06cc\u0646\u06cc\u062a \u0645\u062d\u0627\u0641\u0638\u062a \u0639\u0627\u0645\u0647|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Albania===\n* [[Air Albania]] (51%; 49% Turkish Airlines)\n* [[Albgaz]]\n* [[KESH]]\n* [[OSHEE]]\n* [[Posta Shqiptare]]\n\n===Algeria===\n* [[Air Alg\u00e9rie]]\n* [[Anesrif]]\n* [[Sonatrach]]\n* [[Sonelgaz]]\n\n===Argentina===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Administraci\u00f3n de Infraestructura Ferroviaria]] \n* [[Administraci\u00f3n de Recursos Humanos Ferroviarios]]\n* [[Administraci\u00f3n General de Puertos]] Sociedad del Estado\n* [[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]]\n* [[Aguas y Saneamientos Argentinos]]\n* [[Astilleros DOMECQ GARC\u00cdA]]\n* [[Astilleros TANDANOR]]\n* [[Austral L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas - Cielos del Sur]]\n* [[Banco de Inversiones y Comercio Exterior]]\n* [[Banco de la Naci\u00f3n Argentina]]\n* [[Banco Hipotecario]]\n* [[Casa de Moneda de la Rep\u00fablica Argentina|Casa de la Moneda]] \n* [[Combustibles Nucleares Argentinos CONUARSA]]\n* [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda Nacional del Mercado Mayorista de Electricidad]] CAMMESA\n* [[Construcci\u00f3n de Viviendas de la Armada]] COVIARA\n* [[Contenidos P\u00fablicos]] \n* [[Corporaci\u00f3n del Mercado Central de Buenos Aires]]\n* [[Corporaci\u00f3n Interestadual Pulmar\u00ed]]\n* [[Corporaci\u00f3n Puerto Madero]]\n* [[Corredores Argentinos]]\n* [[Correo Argentino]]\n* {{ill|Dioxitek S.A.|es}}\n* {{ill|Educ.ar|es}}\n* [[Emprendimientos Energ\u00e9ticos Binacionales]] \n* [[Empresa Argentina de Navegaci\u00f3n A\u00e9rea]]\n* [[Empresa de Cargas A\u00e9reas del Atl\u00e1ntico Sud]] \n* [[Empresa Neuquina de Ingenier\u00eda Nuclear]]\n* [[Energ\u00eda Argentina]] S.A ENARSA \n* [[F\u00e1brica Argentina de Aviones]]\n* [[Fabricaciones Militares]]\n* [[Ferrocarriles Argentinos (2015)|Ferrocarriles Argentinos]]\n* [[Fondo de Capital Social]] S.E \n* [[INTERCARGO]] S.A.C  \n* [[INTESA]]\n* [[Investigaciones Aplicadas]] INVAP S.E \n* [[L\u00edneas A\u00e9reas del Estado]] LADE\n* [[Nucleoel\u00e9ctrica Argentina]]\n* [[Operadora Ferroviaria]] \n* [[Polo Tecnol\u00f3gico Constituyentes]]\n* [[Radio de la Universidad Nacional del Litoral]]\n* [[Radio y Televisi\u00f3n Argentina]]\n* [[Radio y Televisi\u00f3n de la Universidad Nacional de C\u00f3rdoba]]\n* [[Soluciones Satelitales Argentinas]] ARSAT\n* [[T\u00e9lam]]\n* [[Yacimientos de Agua de Dionisio]]\n* [[Yacimientos Carboniferos R\u00edo Turbio]]\n* [[YPF]] \n* [[YPF GAS]]\n* [[YPF Tecnolog\u00eda]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n===Australia===\nDefence Housing Australia\n{{main|State-owned enterprises of Australia}}\n\n===Austria===\n* [[\u00d6BB]] (national railway system of Austria, administrator of [[Liechtenstein]]'s railways)\n* [[ASFINAG]] (Autobahn and highway financing, building, maintaining and administration)\n* [[Heta Asset Resolution|Hypo Alpe-Adria-Bank International]]: Austria nationalised this bank in 2009, and in 2014 its then-[[Werner Faymann|Chancellor]] feared its insolvency might have a similar effect to the [[Creditanstalt]] event of 1931.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-02-17/austria-s-faymann-channels-1931-creditanstalt-crash-on-hypo-alpe.html|title=Faymann Evokes 1931 Austria Creditanstalt Crash on Hypo Alpe|first=Boris |last=Groendahl|date=17 February 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Verbund]] 51% SOE (electricity generator and provider)\n* [[Volksbank]] 43.3% SOE (retail banking group, with additional operations in Hungary, Romania and Malta) \n* [[ORF (broadcaster)|ORF]]: funded from television licence fee revenue, dominant player in the Austrian broadcast media\n* [[\u00d6sterreichische Industrieholding]] (\u00d6IAG): Austrian industry-holding stock corporation for partially or entirely nationalized companies, as of 2005:\n** 31.50% of the oil producer [[OMV]]: an integrated international oil and gas company\n** 28.42% of [[Telekom Austria]]: fixed line, mobile, data, and Internet communications services\n** 52.85% of [[\u00d6sterreichische Post]]: postal services\n** 100% of \u00d6IAG-Bergbauholding\n** 100% of Finanzmarkt Beteiligungs AG (FIMBAG)\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n*[[Azerbaijan Airlines|Azerbaijani Airlines]]\n* [[Azerenerji]]\n* [[Az\u0259rpo\u00e7t]]\n* Pasha Construction\n* SOCAR\n\n===Bangladesh===\n* [[Bangladesh Submarine Cable Company Limited]]\n* [[Gas Transmission Company Limited]]\n* [[Karnaphuli Paper Mills]]\n* [[Petrobangla]]\n* [[Biman Bangladesh Airlines]]\n* [[Bangladesh Bank]]\n* [[Bangladesh Jute Mills Corporation]]\n* [[Bangladesh Parjatan Corporation]]\n* [[Bangladesh Ordnance Factory]]\n* [[Bangladesh Steel and Engineering Corporation]]\n* [[Bangladesh Shipping Corporation]]\n\n=== Belgium ===\n* [[Belfius]] (100%)\n* [[Belgischer Rundfunk]]\n* [[Bpost]]\n* [[Brussels Airport]] (25%)\n* [[Elia System Operator]] (5.37%)\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Ethias|nl}} (25%)\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Federale Participatie- en Investeringsmaatschappij|nl}}-{{Interlanguage link multi|Federale Participatie- en Investeringsmaatschappij|fr}} (SFPI-FPIM)\n* [[Fluxys]] (2.1%)\n* [[Infrabel]]\n* [[National Railway Company of Belgium]]\n* [[Belgacom|Proximus]] (53.3%)\n* [[RTBF]]\n* [[Vlaamse Radio- en Televisieomroeporganisatie]]\n\nRegion of [[Wallonia]] owns:\n* [[Brussels South Charleroi Airport]]\n* [[Li\u00e8ge Airport]]\n\n===Belize===\n* [[National Bank of Belize]]\n\n===Brazil===\n{{main|List of Brazilian government enterprises}}\nState-owned enterprises are divided into public enterprises (''empresa p\u00fablica'') and mixed-economy companies (''sociedade de economia mista''). The public enterprises are subdivided into two categories: individual &ndash; with its own assets and [[Share capital|capital]] owned by the [[Federal government of Brazil|Union]] &ndash; and plural companies &ndash; whose assets are owned by multiple government agencies and the Union, which have the majority of the voting interest. [[Caixa Econ\u00f4mica Federal]], [[Correios]], [[Empresa Brasileira de Pesquisa Agropecu\u00e1ria|Embrapa]], [[Brazilian Development Bank|BNDES]] and [[University of S\u00e3o Paulo|USP]] are examples of public enterprises. Mixed-economy companies are enterprises with the majority of stocks owned by the government, but that also have stocks owned by the [[private sector]] and usually have their shares traded on [[stock exchange]]s. [[Banco do Brasil]], [[Petrobras]], [[Sabesp]], and [[Eletrobras]] are examples of mixed-economy companies.\n\nBeginning in the 1990s, the central government of Brazil launched a privatization program inspired by the [[Washington Consensus]]. State-owned enterprises such as [[Vale (mining company)|Vale do Rio Doce]], [[Telebr\u00e1s]], [[Companhia Sider\u00fargica Nacional|CSN]], and [[Usiminas]] (most of them mixed-economy companies) were transferred to the private sector as part of this policy.\n\nBrasil State Owned Companies Fact Sheet / Download from the planejamento.gov.br website.<ref>http://www.planejamento.gov.br/secretarias/upload/Arquivos/dest/perfil_empresas_estatais/2014/2015_ano_base_2014.pdf</ref>\n\n===Brunei===\n* [[Brunei Investment Agency]]\n\n===Bulgaria===\n* [[Bulgarian Energy Holding]]\n* [[Bulgarian Posts]]\n* [[Bulgarian State Railways]]\n* [[LB Bulgaricum]]\n* [[National Railway Infrastructure Company]]\n* [[Kintex]]\n* [[Sofia Airport]]\n\n===Canada===\n{{main article|Crown corporations of Canada}}\nIn [[Canada]], state-owned corporations are referred to as ''Crown corporations'', indicating that an organization is established by law, owned by the sovereign (either [[Monarchy of Canada|in right of Canada]] or [[Monarchy in the Canadian provinces|a province]]), and overseen by parliament and cabinet. Examples of federal Crown corporations include:\n* the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]\n* [[Canada Post]]\n* [[Bank of Canada]]\n* [[Telefilm Canada]]\n* [[Via Rail]]\n\n[[Minister of the Crown|Ministers of the Crown]] often control the [[share (finance)|shares]] in such public corporations, while parliament both sets out the laws that create and bind Crown corporations and sets their annual budgets.\n\nForeign SOEs are welcome to invest in Canada: in fall 2013, British Columbia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.news.gov.bc.ca/news_releases_2013-2017/2013PREM0091-001365.htm|title=Premier Clark announces Jobs and Trade Mission to Asia|author=Office of the Premier, International Trade, and Minister Responsible for the Asia Pacific Strategy and Multiculturalism|publisher=|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/industry-news/energy-and-resources/bc-minister-says-malaysian-investment-vindicates-provinces-bets-on-lng-sector/article14726740/|title=B.C. minister says Malaysian investment vindicates province\u2019s bets on LNG sector|work=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> and Alberta<ref>[https://edmontonjournal.com/news/Redford+trip+China+highlights+petrochemical+potential/8924810/story.html \"Redford\u2019s trip to China highlights petrochemical potential\"], ''edmontonjournal.com'', 17 Sep 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calgarysun.com/2013/09/17/alberta-premier-alison-redford-says-chinas-investors-want-more-details-on-rules-and-guidelines|title=Alberta Premier Alison Redford says China's investors want more details on rules|work=Calgary Sun|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://energyasia.com/blog/china-canadas-alberta-province-signs-ceremonial-framework-agreement-expand-energy-ties-amid-waning-chinese-interest/|title=CHINA: Canada\u2019s Alberta province signs framework agreement to expand energy ties amid waning Chinese interest|work=EnergyAsia|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref> signed agreements overseas to promote foreign direct investment in Canada. The [[Investment Canada Act]] governs this area federally. Former Prime Minister Stephen Harper stated in 2013 that the \"government [needs] to exercise its judgement\" over SOEs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/business/2013/11/08/foreign_investment_doesnt_need_absolute_clarity_harper.html|title=Foreign investment doesn\u2019t need \u2018absolute clarity: Harper|date=8 November 2013|work=thestar.com|accessdate=12 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nSaskatchewan has maintained the largest number of Crown corporations, including:\n* [[Saskatchewan Government Insurance]]\n* [[SaskEnergy]]\n* [[SaskPower]]\n* [[SaskTel]]\n* [[SaskWater]]\n\nCrown corporations of British Columbia include:\n* [[BC Hydro]]\n* [[BC Transit]]\n* BC Housing Management Commission\n* [[British Columbia Lottery Corporation]]\n* [[Liquor Distribution Branch]]\n\nIn Ontario:\n* [[TFO|GroupeM\u00e9dia TFO]]\n* [[Independent Electricity System Operator]]\n* [[TVOntario|Ontario Educational Communications Authority]]\n* [[Ontario Lottery and Gaming Corporation]]\n* [[Ontario Power Generation]]\n* [[Liquor Control Board of Ontario]]\nIn Quebec:\n* [[Caisse de d\u00e9p\u00f4t et placement du Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Hydro-Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Investissement Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Loto-Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de la Place des Arts de Montr\u00e9al]]\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des alcools du Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Traversiers du Qu\u00e9bec]]\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Qu\u00e9b\u00e9coise des Infrastructures]]\n* [[T\u00e9l\u00e9-Qu\u00e9bec]]\n\nPrivatization, or the selling of Crown corporations to private interests, has become common throughout Canada over the past 30 years. [[Petro-Canada]], [[Canadian National Railway]], and [[Air Canada]] are examples of former federal Crown corporations that have been privatized. Privatized provincial Crown corporations include [[Alberta Government Telephones]] (which merged with privately owned [[BC Tel]] to form [[Telus]]), [[BCRIC]], [[Manitoba Telecom Services]], [[Saskatchewan Oil & Gas Corporation]] and [[Potash Corporation of Saskatchewan]].\n\n===China===\n{{main|List of government-owned companies of China}}\nAfter 1949, all business entities in the [[People's Republic of China]] were created and owned by the government. In the late 1980s, the government began to reform the state-owned enterprise, and during the 1990s and 2000s, many mid-sized and small sized state-owned enterprises were privatized and went public. There are a number of different corporate forms which result in a mixture of public and private capital. In PRC terminology, a state-owned enterprise refers to a particular corporate form, which is increasingly being replaced by the [[public company|listed company]].{{fact|date=January 2017}} State-owned enterprises are mostly governed by both local governments' SASAC and, in the central government, [[State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission of the State Council|the State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission (SASAC) of the State Council]]. However, some state-owned enterprise were governed by [[China Investment Corporation]] (and its domestic arm [[Central Huijin Investment]]), as well as under the governance of [[Ministry of Education of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Education]] for the university-run enterprises, or some financial institutes that were under the governance of the [[Ministry of Finance of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Finance]].\n\nAs of 2011, 35% of business activity and 43% of profits in the People's Republic of China resulted from companies in which the state owned a majority interest. Critics, such as ''The New York Times'', have alleged that China's state-owned companies are a vehicle for corruption by the families of ruling party leaders who have sometimes amassed fortunes while managing them.<ref name=NYT111012>{{cite news|title=China\u2019s Grip on Economy Will Test New Leaders|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/10/world/asia/state-enterprises-pose-test-for-chinas-new-leaders.html|accessdate=November 10, 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 9, 2012|first=Keith |last=Bradsher}}</ref> \n\n==== Hong Kong ====\nIn the postwar years, Hong Kong's colonial government operated under a laissez-faire economic philosophy called [[positive non-interventionism]]. Hence Crown corporations did not play as significant a role in the development of the territory as in many other British territories.\n\nThe [[MTR Corporation]] (MTR) was formed as a Crown corporation, mandated to operate under \"prudent commercial principles\", in 1975. The [[Kowloon-Canton Railway]], operated under a government department, was corporatised in 1982 to imitate the success of MTR (see [[Kowloon-Canton Railway Corporation]]). MTR was privatised in 2000 although the Hong Kong Government is still the majority shareholder. KCR was operationally merged with MTR in 2007.\n\nExamples of present-day statutory bodies include the [[Airport Authority Hong Kong|Airport Authority]], responsible for running the [[Hong Kong International Airport]], or the [[Hong Kong Housing Authority|Housing Authority]], which provides housing to about half of Hong Kong residents.\n\n===Colombia===\n[[File:EDIFICIO EPM.jpg|thumb|[[Empresas P\u00fablicas de Medell\u00edn]] headquarters]]\n* [[Ecopetrol]]\n* [[Empresas P\u00fablicas de Medell\u00edn]]\n* [[ETB (company)|ETB]]\n* [https://www.lasceibas.gov.co/ Las Ceibas - Empresas P\u00fablicas de Neiva E.S.P]\n\n===Cuba===\n* [[ETECSA|Empresa de Telecomunicaciones de Cuba S.A.]]\n* [[Union de Industrias Militares]]\n\n=== Czech Republic ===\n{{main article|St\u00e1tn\u00ed podnik}}\n* [[Budweiser Budvar Brewery]]\n* \u010cEPS, a.s.\n* [[\u010cEZ Group]]\n* [[\u010cesk\u00e9 dr\u00e1hy]]\n\n===Denmark===\n* [[Banedanmark]]\n* [[Danske Spil]]\n* [[DR (broadcaster)|DR]]\n* [[DSB (railway company)|DSB]]\n* [[Energinet.dk]]\n* [[\u00d8rsted (company)|\u00d8rsted]]\n* [[PostNord]] (40%)\n\n'''Municipal'''\n* Aarhus Vand A/S\n* Kalundborg Forsyning A/S\n* Middelgrunden offshore electricity generation wind farm\n* Sams\u00f8 offshore electricity generation wind farm and district heating plants\n* Vandcenter Syd as\n\n===Egypt===\n* [[Egypt Post]]\n* [[EgyptAir]]\n* [[Egyptian National Railways]]\n* [[Nile TV]]\n* [[Suez Canal Authority]]\n* [[Telecom Egypt]]\n* [[EGPC]]\n* [[ERTU]]\n* [[EGAS]]\n* [[Arab Contractors]]\n* [[NBE]]\n\n===Finland===\n{{main|List of Finnish government enterprises}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Alko]]\n* [[Altia]]\n* [[CSC \u2013 IT Center for Science]]\n* [[Destia]]\n* [[Hansel Ltd.]]\n* [[Laatumaa]]\n* [[Mets\u00e4hallitus]]\n* [[National Land Survey of Finland]]\n* [[Omaisuudenhoitoyhti\u00f6 Arsenal]]\n* [[Patria (company)|Patria]]\n* [[Senate Properties]]\n* [[Veikkaus]]\n* [[VR Group]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===France===\n{{main|Agence des participations de l'\u00c9tat}}\n\n===Gabon===\n* [[Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale Petroli\u00e8re Gabonaise]]\n\n===Germany===\n{{main|State-owned enterprises of Germany}}\n\n===Ghana===\n* [[Ghana National Petroleum Corporation]]\n* [[Ghana Oil Company]]\n* [[Volta River Authority]]\n\n===Greenland===\n* [[Greenland Airport Authority]]\n\n===Hungary===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Hungarian State Railways]]\n* [[Kossuth R\u00e1di\u00f3]]\n* [[Magyar Posta]]\n* [[Magyar R\u00e1di\u00f3]]\n* [[Magyar Telev\u00edzi\u00f3]]\n* [[MVM Group]]\n* [[Paks Nuclear Power Plant]]\n* [[State Printing Company]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===India===\n{{main|List of public sector undertakings in India}}\nIn [[India]], state-owned enterprise is termed a [[Public Sector Undertakings in India|Public Sector Undertaking]] (PSU) or a Central Public Sector Enterprise (CPSE). These companies are owned by the [[Government of India|Union Government]], or one of the many [[States and territories of India|state or territorial governments]], or both. The company [[Stock|equity]] needs to be majority owned by the government to be a PSU. Examples are [[Life Insurance Corporation of India]], [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation]], [[Engineers India Limited]], [[India Trade Promotion Organization]], [[GAIL]], [[Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited|BSNL]], [[Food Corporation of India]], [[Air India]], and Bharat Heavy Electrials Limited (BHEL).\n\n===Indonesia===\n{{main|State-owned Enterprise of Indonesia}}\n\n===Iran===\n* [[Iran Air]]\n* [[National Iranian Gas Company]]\n\n===Iraq===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[General Company for Ports of Iraq]]\n* [[Iraq National Oil Company]]\n* [[Iraqi Airways]]\n* [[Iraqi Post]]\n* [[Iraqi Republic Railways]]\n* [[Iraqi Telecommunications and Post Company]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Ireland===\n{{main|State-sponsored bodies of the Republic of Ireland}}\n* [[Bank of Ireland]] (15%)\n\n===Israel===\n[[File:Chandeliers, marble floor, in Jerusalem Central Post Office.JPG|thumb|Central post office and the headquarters of [[Israel Postal Company]] in [[Jerusalem]]]]\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Amidar (company)|Amidar]]\n* [[Israel Aerospace Industries]]\n* [[Israel Aerospace Industries Tamam Division]]\n* [[Israel Airports Authority]]\n* [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]] (including [[Israel Radio]])\n* [[Israel Electric Corporation]]\n* [[Israel Military Industries]]\n* [[Israel Port Authority]]\n* [[Israel Postal Company]]\n* [[Israel Railways]]\n* [[Mekorot]]\n* [[National Roads Company of Israel]]\n* [[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Italy===\nCompanies owned by the [[Ministry of Economy and Finances (Italy)|Ministry of Economy and Finance