ricity]]\n* [[Vietnam Multimedia Corporation]]\n* [[Vietnam Posts and Telecommunications Group]]\n* [[Viettel Mobile]]\n* [[Vietnam Railways]]\n* [[Vinacomin]]\n* [[Vinatex]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Zambia===\n* [[TAZARA Railway]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Companies|Lists}}\n* [[:Category:Government-owned companies by country|Government-owned companies by country]] <small>(category)</small>\n* [[List of government-owned airlines]]\n* [[List of privatizations]]\n* [[:Category:Lists of companies|Lists of companies]] <small>(category)</small>\n* [[National oil company]]\n* [[State ownership]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{citation|title=Profiles of Existing Government Corporations\u2014A Study Prepared by the U.S. General Accounting Office for the Committee on Government Operations| publication-date=1988 | id= GAO/AFMD-89-43FS Document: H402-4| location= Washington, DC|publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office| url = http://www.gao.gov/assets/90/88616.pdf| format = pdf |page = 301}}.  [http://www.yumpu.com/en/document/view/6535622/profiles-of-existing-government-corporations-us-government- Alternate location:]\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline|Government-owned companies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Government-owned companies}}\n[[Category:Government-owned companies| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of companies]]\n[[Category:Lists of government-owned companies| ]]\n", "name_user": "Mohamed maximum77", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEgypt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_government-owned_companies"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Sheila Bellush", "text_new": "[[Image:SheilaBellush.jpg|right|thumbnail|220px|Sheila Bellush with her husband Jamie and her four youngest children]]\n\nSheila Bellush was a 35-year-old mother of six who was murdered on November 7, 1997, by a hired gunman named Jose Del Toro, on the orders of her ex-husband, Allen Blackthorne. Blackthorne, who had stalked Bellush since their divorce in 1987, allegedly wanted custody of their two children.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/010500/TampaBay/Bellush_s_former_husb.shtml|title=Bellush's former husband indicted|first1=Wes|last1=Allison|first2=Anita|last2=Kumar|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20000301013646/http://www.sptimes.com/News/010500/TampaBay/Bellush_s_former_husb.shtml|archive-date=March 1, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 14, 2007|year=January 5, 2000|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSheila Leigh Walsh was born on October 19, 1962 in [[Topeka, Kansas]]. She married Blackthorne in 1982, and had two daughters, Stevie and Daryl. Their divorce was not amicable, with each accusing the other of abusing their children. Sheila married Jamie Bellush in 1993, and had quadruplets two years later. They moved to Sarasota, Florida to escape the constant surveillance of her ex-husband.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\"/>\n\n==Murder==\nBlackthorne was unhappy with his divorce from Sheila and began to harass her after she won custody of their children. When the Bellush family moved to Florida, he tracked her down using a private investigator and plotted to hire a man to beat her up. Blackthorne asked Daniel Alex Rocha, a golfing acquaintance with a minor criminal history, for help. Rocha was allegedly motivated to carry out the crime when told by Blackthorne that Sheila was abusing the two children, Stevie and Daryl.<ref name=\"48 Hours\">{{cite episode|title=Justice for Sheila?|network=[[CBS]]|series=[[48 Hours (TV program)|48 Hours]]|date=May 12, 1999|season=6|number=33}}</ref> Rocha then contacted a friend, Samuel Gonzales, who introduced him to his cousin, Jose Luis Del Toro, who agreed to do the attack for $14,000.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\"/><ref>{{Cite episode|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/american-justice-2002/episode-8-season-11/brutal-revenge/194507/|series=[[American Justice]]|season=11|number=8|network=[[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]|title=Brutal Revenge|last=Kurtis|first=Bill (Host)|date=June 5, 2002|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 1997, Del Toro traveled to [[Sarasota, Florida]], in a car registered to his grandmother, with the intention of assaulting Sheila. He stopped at a [[Sports Authority]] store to obtain camouflage clothes and a [[gas station]] for directions to the address Rocha gave.<ref name=\"SPTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/070700/State/Del_Toro_admits_the_m.shtml|title=Del Toro admits the murder|date=July 7, 2000|first=Jounice|last=Nealy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817224728/http://www.sptimes.com/News/070700/State/Del_Toro_admits_the_m.shtml|archive-date=August 17, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 14, 2007|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]}}</ref> On his way to Bellush's house, Del Toro was spotted by a neighbor who memorized the license plate (this would later lead to his capture). Del Toro continued to the Sarasota home, where he broke in and saw Sheila with the quadruplets. In an interview with police before his conviction, he told them that said he saw her with her children and saw how caring she was and almost didn't go through with it. He was about to leave, but Sheila noticed the door was open and then noticed him. Del Toro stated he couldn't run, so he shot Bellush in the face with a [[.45 Caliber|.45 caliber]] gun and slit her throat in full view of the quadruplets.<ref name=\"SPTimes\"/> Her body was found a few hours later by 13-year-old Stevie when she returned from school.<ref>{{cite web|last=Minai|first=Leanora|title=Daughter recalls finding mother slain|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=June 13, 2000|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/061300/State/Daughter_recalls_find.shtml| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000711040728/http://www.sptimes.com/News/061300/State/Daughter_recalls_find.shtml|archive-date=July 11, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=March 24, 2012}}</ref> The quadruplets had been walking around in Sheila's blood, leaving small bloody footprints all over the crime scene.<ref name=first>{{cite podcast|url=https://www.podcastone.com/episode/Justice-The-Sheila-Bellush-Story-Part-II |title=Justice: The Sheila Bellush Story, Part II|work=The First Degree |publisher=PodcastOne |last1=Vanek|first1=Jac|last2=Linkletter|first2=Alexis|last3=Jensen|first3=Billy |date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Several of the quadruplets were wearing life vests, which Sheila would put on them if she had to change one child's diaper so if the other children wandered off unattended and fell into the backyard pool, they wouldn't drown.<ref name=first />\n\n==Aftermath==\nJose Del Toro fled to [[Mexico]] after committing the murder. He was extradited to the [[United States]] in July 1999, and pleaded guilty to [[first-degree murder]] and [[gun|armed]] [[burglary]] charges in 2000 in Florida. Circuit Judge Paul Logan gave Del Toro two consecutive [[life sentence]]s, the maximum penalty for both charges. Gonzalez pleaded guilty to [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy to commit murder]] in June 1998 in a [[plea bargain]]; he was sentenced to 19 years in prison. Rocha opted to go to trial instead and was convicted of first-degree murder in January 1999 with Gonzalez's testimony; he received a life sentence.<ref name=\"SPTimes\"/>\n\nAllen Blackthorne was convicted of federal charges of interstate conspiracy to commit murder and interstate domestic violence. He received two concurrent life sentences without the possibility of parole, starting at the [[United States Penitentiary, Beaumont|Beaumont, Texas federal prison]]. In 2001, Blackthorne was nearly killed during an attack by a prison gang, after which he was segregated from the general prison population and eventually transferred to a Florida facility. Blackthorne died aged 59 on November 18, 2014, at the federal prison  in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]. The cause of death in the case was not released.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/crime/ex-millionaire-who-plotted-his-ex-wifes-sarasota-murder-dies-in-prison/2207417/ |title=Millionaire who plotted ex-wife's notorious Sarasota murder dies in prison|work=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|date=November 21, 2014|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nThe books ''Every Breath You Take'' ({{ISBN|9780743439749}}) by [[Ann Rule]] and ''The Truth is Stronger Than a Lie'' ({{ISBN|0975318519}}) by Khari Imo are about this case. The case inspired the episode \"The Hired Help\" of the series ''[[Behind Mansion Walls]]'', presented by [[Investigation Discovery]], and a 2002 episode of [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]'s ''[[American Justice]]'', titled \"Brutal Revenge\" (since repackaged for [[The Biography Channel]] under the series title ''Notorious''). This case was also illustrated in a 2011 episode of the [[Investigation Discovery]] Channel series ''FBI: Criminal Pursuit'', titled \"Twisted Obsession\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Episode Detail: Obsession - The Investigators|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=198009&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=3625649|website=tvguide.com|accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2015, ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours]]: Hard Evidence'' (''48 Hours: Mystery/Investigation'') on [[Investigation Discovery]] released an episode entitled \"Justice for Sheila.\" [[Investigation Discovery]] series ''[[Nothing Personal (TV series)|Nothing Personal]]: Murder for Hire'' aired an episode titled \"Deadly Divorce\" in 2011.<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z9asltbJxZw |network=[[Investigation Discovery]]|series=[[Nothing Personal (TV series)|Nothing Personal]]|title=Deadly Divorce|season=1|number=6|last=Schirripa|first=Steve (Host)|via=[[YouTube]]|date=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellush, Sheila}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:American murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Florida]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Florida]]\n[[Category:Deaths by stabbing in Florida]]\n[[Category:1997 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:1997 in Florida]]\n[[Category:November 1997 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:SheilaBellush.jpg|right|thumbnail|220px|Sheila Bellush with her husband Jamie and her four youngest children]]\n\nSheila Bellush was a 35-year-old mother of six who was murdered on November 7, 1997, by a hired gunman named Jose Del Toro, on the orders of her ex-husband, Allen Blackthorne. Blackthorne, who had stalked Bellush since their divorce in 1987, allegedly wanted custody of their two children.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/010500/TampaBay/Bellush_s_former_husb.shtml|title=Bellush's former husband indicted|first1=Wes|last1=Allison|first2=Anita|last2=Kumar|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20000301013646/http://www.sptimes.com/News/010500/TampaBay/Bellush_s_former_husb.shtml|archive-date=March 1, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 14, 2007|year=January 5, 2000|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSheila Leigh Walsh was born on October 19, 1962 in [[Topeka, Kansas]]. She married Blackthorne in 1982, and had two daughters, Stevie and Daryl. Their divorce was not amicable, with each accusing the other of abusing their children. Sheila married Jamie Bellush in 1993, and had quadruplets two years later. They moved to Sarasota, Florida to escape the constant surveillance of her ex-husband.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\"/>\n\n==Murder==\nBlackthorne was unhappy with his divorce from Sheila and began to harass her after she won custody of their children. When the Bellush family moved to Florida, he tracked her down using a private investigator and plotted to hire a man to beat her up. Blackthorne asked Daniel Alex Rocha, a golfing acquaintance with a minor criminal history, for help. Rocha was allegedly motivated to carry out the crime when told by Blackthorne that Sheila was abusing the two children, Stevie and Daryl.<ref name=\"48 Hours\">{{cite episode|title=Justice for Sheila?|network=[[CBS]]|series=[[48 Hours (TV program)|48 Hours]]|date=May 12, 1999|season=6|number=33}}</ref> Rocha then contacted a friend, Samuel Gonzales, who introduced him to his cousin, Jose Luis Del Toro, who agreed to do the attack for $14,000.<ref name=\"SPTimes2\"/><ref>{{Cite episode|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/american-justice-2002/episode-8-season-11/brutal-revenge/194507/|series=[[American Justice]]|season=11|number=8|network=[[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]|title=Brutal Revenge|last=Kurtis|first=Bill (Host)|date=June 5, 2002|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, 1997, Del Toro traveled to [[Sarasota, Florida]], in a car registered to his grandmother, with the intention of assaulting Sheila. He stopped at a [[Sports Authority]] store to obtain camouflage clothes and a [[gas station]] for directions to the address Rocha gave.<ref name=\"SPTimes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/070700/State/Del_Toro_admits_the_m.shtml|title=Del Toro admits the murder|date=July 7, 2000|first=Jounice|last=Nealy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000817224728/http://www.sptimes.com/News/070700/State/Del_Toro_admits_the_m.shtml|archive-date=August 17, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 14, 2007|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]}}</ref> On his way to Bellush's house, Del Toro was spotted by a neighbor who memorized the license plate (this would later lead to his capture). Del Toro continued to the Sarasota home, where he broke in and saw Sheila with the quadruplets. In an interview with police before his conviction, he told them that said he saw her with her children and saw how caring she was and almost didn't go through with it. He was about to leave, but Sheila noticed the door was open and then noticed him. Del Toro stated he couldn't run, so he shot Bellush in the face with a [[.45 Caliber|.45 caliber]] gun and slit her throat in full view of the quadruplets.<ref name=\"SPTimes\"/> Her body was found a few hours later by 13-year-old Stevie when she returned from school.<ref>{{cite web|last=Minai|first=Leanora|title=Daughter recalls finding mother slain|work=[[Tampa Bay Times|St. Petersburg Times]]|date=June 13, 2000|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/061300/State/Daughter_recalls_find.shtml| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20000711040728/http://www.sptimes.com/News/061300/State/Daughter_recalls_find.shtml|archive-date=July 11, 2000|url-status=dead|accessdate=March 24, 2012}}</ref> The quadruplets had been walking around in Sheila's blood, leaving small bloody footprints all over the crime scene.<ref name=first>{{cite podcast|url=https://www.podcastone.com/episode/Justice-The-Sheila-Bellush-Story-Part-II |title=Justice: The Sheila Bellush Story, Part II|work=The First Degree |publisher=PodcastOne |last1=Vanek|first1=Jac|last2=Linkletter|first2=Alexis|last3=Jensen|first3=Billy |date=April 1, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> Several of the quadruplets were wearing life vests, which Sheila would put on them if she had to change one child's diaper so if the other children wandered off unattended and fell into the backyard pool, they wouldn't drown.<ref name=first />\n\n==Aftermath==\nJose Del Toro fled to [[Mexico]] after committing the murder. He was extradited to the [[United States]] in July 1999, and pleaded guilty to [[first-degree murder]] and [[gun|armed]] [[burglary]] charges in 2000 in Florida. Circuit Judge Paul Logan gave Del Toro two consecutive [[life sentence]]s, the maximum penalty for both charges. Gonzalez pleaded guilty to [[conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy to commit murder]] in June 1998 in a [[plea bargain]]; he was sentenced to 19 years in prison. Rocha opted to go to trial instead and was convicted of first-degree murder in January 1999 with Gonzalez's testimony; he received a life sentence.<ref name=\"SPTimes\"/>\n\nAllen Blackthorne was convicted of federal charges of interstate conspiracy to commit murder and interstate domestic violence. He received two concurrent life sentences without the possibility of parole, starting at the [[United States Penitentiary, Beaumont|Beaumont, Texas federal prison]]. In 2001, Blackthorne was nearly killed during an attack by a prison gang, after which he was segregated from the general prison population and eventually transferred to a Florida facility. Blackthorne died aged 59 on November 18, 2014, at the federal prison  in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]]. The cause of death in the case was not released.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/publicsafety/crime/ex-millionaire-who-plotted-his-ex-wifes-sarasota-murder-dies-in-prison/2207417/ |title=Millionaire who plotted ex-wife's notorious Sarasota murder dies in prison|work=[[Tampa Bay Times]]|date=November 21, 2014|accessdate=November 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Portrayals==\nThe books ''Every Breath You Take'' ({{ISBN|9780743439749}}) by [[Ann Rule]] and ''The Truth is Stronger Than a Lie'' ({{ISBN|0975318519}}) by Khari Imo are about this case. The case inspired the episode \"The Hired Help\" of the series ''[[Behind Mansion Walls]]'', presented by [[Investigation Discovery]], and a 2002 episode of [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]]'s ''[[American Justice]]'', titled \"Brutal Revenge\" (since repackaged for [[The Biography Channel]] under the series title ''Notorious''). This case was also illustrated in a 2011 episode of the [[Investigation Discovery]] Channel series ''FBI: Criminal Pursuit'', titled \"Twisted Obsession\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Episode Detail: Obsession - The Investigators|url=http://www.tvguide.com/detail/tv-show.aspx?tvobjectid=198009&more=ucepisodelist&episodeid=3625649|website=tvguide.com|accessdate=November 22, 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2015, ''[[48 Hours (TV series)|48 Hours]]: Hard Evidence'' (''48 Hours: Mystery/Investigation'') on [[Investigation Discovery]] released an episode entitled \"Justice for Sheila.\" [[Investigation Discovery]] series ''[[Nothing Personal]]: Murder for Hire'' aired an episode titled \"Deadly Divorce\" in 2011.<ref>{{cite episode|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z9asltbJxZw |network=[[Investigation Discovery]]|series=[[Nothing Personal (TV series)|Nothing Personal]]|title=Deadly Divorce|season=1|number=6|last=Schirripa|first=Steve (Host)|via=[[YouTube]]|date=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bellush, Sheila}}\n\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:American murder victims]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Florida]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Florida]]\n[[Category:Deaths by stabbing in Florida]]\n[[Category:1997 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:1997 in Florida]]\n[[Category:November 1997 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Nothing Personal\u2192Nothing Personal (TV series)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Murder_of_Sheila_Bellush"}
{"title_page": "1999 Major League Soccer season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox football league season\n  | season                     = '''1999'''\n  | mlscup                     = [[D.C. United]] (3rd title)\n  | shield                     = [[D.C. United]] (2nd shield)\n  | league topscorer           = [[Stern John]]<br>[[Roy Lassiter]]<br>[[Jason Kreis]]<br>(18 goals)\n  | matches                    = 192\n  | total goals                = 549\n  | average goals              = \n  | biggest home win           =\n  | biggest away win           =\n  | highest scoring            =\n  | longest wins               =\n  | longest unbeaten           =\n  | longest losses             =\n  | highest attendance         = [[Columbus Crew SC|Columbus Crew]]<br>Season: 283,129<br>Game Avg.: 17,696 \n  | lowest attendance          = [[Sporting Kansas City|Kansas City Wizards]]<br>Season: 130,924<br>Game Avg.: 8,183 \n  | attendance                 = 2,742,102\n  | average attendance         = 14,282\n  | prevseason                 = [[1998 Major League Soccer season|1998]]\n  | nextseason                 = [[2000 Major League Soccer season|2000]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1999 Major League Soccer season''' was the fourth season in [[Major League Soccer]]'s history. This was the last season which used the 35 yard line shootout rule to resolve tied games, and that of the countdown timer, with [[MLS Cup 1999]] adopting the IFAB-standard running clock thereafter.\n\n==Final standings==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=\"170\"|Eastern Conference\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| P | Played}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| W | Win}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip|(sw)|Shootout Win}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip|(sl)|Shootout Loss}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| L | Loss}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GD | Goal difference}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Pts | Points}}\n|-\n|align=left|s - [[D.C. United]]\n|32||23||6||3||9||65||43||+22||57\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[Columbus Crew]]\n|32||19||6||4||13||48||39||+9||45\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[Tampa Bay Mutiny]]\n|32||14||5||7||18||51||50||+1||32\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[Miami Fusion]]\n|32||13||5||4||19||42||59||\u201317||29\n|-\n|align=left|[[New England Revolution]]\n|32||12||5||7||20||38||53||\u201315||26\n|-\n|align=left|[[MetroStars]]\n|32||7||3||5||25||32||64||\u201332||15\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!width=\"170\"|Western Conference\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| P | Played}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| W | Win}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip|(sw)|Shootout Win}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip|(sl)|Shootout Loss}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| L | Loss}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GF | Goals for}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GA | Goals against}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| GD | Goal difference}}\n!width=\"40\"|{{Tooltip| Pts | Points}}\n|-\n|align=left|y - [[LA Galaxy|Los Angeles Galaxy]]\n|32||20||3||4||12||49||29||+20||54\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[FC Dallas|Dallas Burn]]\n|32||19||3||6||13||54||35||+19||51\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[Chicago Fire Soccer Club|Chicago Fire]]\n|32||18||3||5||14||51||36||+15||48\n|-\n|align=left|x - [[Colorado Rapids]]\n|32||20||6||3||12||38||39||\u20131||48\n|-\n|align=left|[[San Jose Clash]]\n|32||19||10||3||13||48||49||\u20131||37\n|-\n|align=left|[[Kansas City Wizards]]\n|32||8||2||6||24||33||53||\u201320||20\n|}\n\n*The top four teams in each conference make the playoffs.<br>'''Wins (W)''' are worth 3 points.<br>'''Shootout Wins (SW)''' are worth 1 point, and is considered a Win in the standings.<br>'''Shootout Loss (SL)''' are worth 0 points, and is considered a Loss in the standings.<br>'''Loss (L)''' are worth 0 points.\n*s = Supporters Shield winner\n*y = Conference Leader\n*x = Clinched playoff berth\n\n==MLS Cup Playoffs==\n===Bracket===\n{{8TeamBracket-MLS Divisional Version 1\n| RD1='''Conference Semifinals''