{"title_page": "Josephine Siao", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{infobox person\n| name = Josephine Siao\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name        = \u856d\u82b3\u82b3\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name = Siao Loeng (\u856d\u4eae)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|3|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Shanghai]], China\n| nationality = Australia| alma_mater = [[Seton Hall University]]<br>[[Regis University]]\n| occupation = Actress, television personality\n| years_active = 1954\u20131997\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Charlie Chin]]|1976|1978|reason=div}}<br>{{marriage|Clarence Chang|1980}}\n| children = Chang Hoi-kam (daughter)<br>Chang Nga-kam (daughter)\n| parents = Xiao Naizhen (father)<br>Cheng Fenghui (mother)\n| awards = {{Awards|award=Best Child Actor|year=1955|title=The Orphan Girl|role=Mui Kit (childhood)|name=[[Asia-Pacific Film Festival]]}}{{Awards|award=[[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]|year=1996|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun|name=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]}}{{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1996|title=Hu-Du-Men|role=Lang Kim-sum|name=Asia-Pacific Film Festival}}<br>{{awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]|year=1988|title=[[The Wrong Couples]]|role=Wong Mui|year2=1996|title2=[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]|role2=May Sun}}{{Awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Award for Lifetime Achievement|Lifetime Achievement Award]]|year=2009}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Bauhinia Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1996|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun}}}}{{awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Critics Society Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1995|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun}}}}{{awards|award=[[Asian Film Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Outstanding Contribution to Asian Cinema|year=2007}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Horse Film Festival and Awards|Golden Horse Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Golden Horse Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]|year=1975|title=Girl Friend|role=Meng Ya-ping}}{{Awards|award=[[Golden Horse Award for Best Leading Actress|Best Leading Actress]]|year=1995|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun|year2=1996|title2=[[Hu-Du-Men]]|role2=Lang Kim-sum}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Bell Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Golden Bell Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]|year=1995|title=Autumn Water & Vast Sky|role=Hsiang I-hung}}}}\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| t = \u856d\u82b3\u82b3\n| s = \u8427\u82b3\u82b3\n| p = Xi\u0101o F\u0101ngf\u0101ng\n| j = siu1 fong1 fong1\n}}\n| module2 = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| alias = Sister Fong-fong (\u82b3\u82b3\u59d0)\n | background = temporary\n| origin = [[British Hong Kong]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Josephine Siao Fong-fong''' {{post-nominals|MBE}} ({{Lang-zh|s=\u8427\u82b3\u82b3|t=\u856d\u82b3\u82b3|p=Xi\u0101o F\u0101ngf\u0101ng|j=siu1 fong1 fong1}}) is a Hong Kong film star who became popular as a child actress and continued her success as a mature actress, winning numerous awards including Best Actress at the [[45th Berlin International Film Festival]] (for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'').<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/archive/jahresarchive/1995/03_preistraeger_1995/03_preistraeger_1995.html |title=Berlinale: 1995 Prize Winners |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Since retiring from show business (partly due to her increasing deafness), she has become a writer and a psychologist, known for her work against child abuse.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Avenue of Stars Siao Fong Fong.JPG|right|thumb|Hand prints of Siao Fong-fong on the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong]]]]\nJosephine Siao Fong-fong was born as Siao Liang in [[Shanghai]], with her ancestral home in [[Luzhi]], [[Suzhou]], Jiangsu. At the age of two, she was brought to Hong Kong by her parents.\n\nSiao's first movie appearance was at age six, and she became one of the biggest teen idols in Hong Kong during the late 1960s, along with frequent co-star [[Connie Chan Po-chu]]. The two were often cast in [[wuxia]] films as disciples of the same master and sometimes\u2014when Connie played the male lead\u2014as young heroes in love. Back in the 1960s, Josephine's and Connie's fans maintained a heated rivalry. News of their fans getting into catfights was not uncommon in those days.\n\nUnlike many child stars, Siao made a successful transition to adult stardom, remaining one of Hong Kong's most prolific and popular actresses.  She was also one of the directors (co-directing with Leung Po-Chih \u6881\u666e\u667a) and writers of ''[[Jumping Ash]]'' (\u8df3\u7070). This film is regarded as a prelude to the [[Hong Kong New Wave]] in the 1980s by film critics.\n\nHaving largely missed out on formal education because of her acting career as a child, Siao pursued her studies in later years despite the handicap of increasing deafness and the demands of raising a family (she has two daughters by her second husband).  During this time she made fewer films, but her output included highly praised work such as her award-winning performance in ''Summer Snow'' (1995) as a middle-aged widow trying to cope with her father-in-law suffering from Alzheimer's Disease.\n\nWestern fans of [[martial arts film]]s will probably know her best from the [[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|''Fong Sai-yuk'' films]] made in 1993, in which she played [[Jet Li]]'s [[kung fu]]\u2013fighting mother. (These films were released on Western DVD as ''The Legend''.)\n\nSiao has been retired from show business since 1997 in favour of her work in child psychology.  In particular, she is a noted campaigner against child abuse, and founded the End Child Sexual Abuse Foundation, which she now chairs, in 1999.  She is also a published author.\n\nSome of the milestones in her life include:\n* 1970: Bachelor's degree in Mass Communications and Asian Studies at [[Seton Hall University]]\n* 1974: won the best actress award at Spain Film Festival and Taiwan Film Festival\n* 1990: obtained a master's degree in child psychology from [[Regis University]]\n* 1995: won the best actress award at the Berlin Film Festival for ''Summer Snow''\n* 1996: member of the Most Excellent [[Order of the British Empire]]\n* 2009: Life Achievement Award of the [[28th Hong Kong Film Awards]]\n\n== Selective filmography ==\n* ''[[An Orphan's Tragedy]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Rhythm of the Wave]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Jumping Ash]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Lam Au Chun]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Spooky Bunch]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Plain Jane to the Rescue]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[The Perfect Match (1982 film)|The Perfect Match]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[A Friend from Inner Space]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[The Wrong Couples]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Fist of Fury 1991]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Fist of Fury 1991 II]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Too Happy for Words]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|Fong Sai Yuk]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Fong Sai-yuk II]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Always on My Mind]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Kin Chan No Cinema Jack]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Hu-Du-Men]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Mahjong Dragon]]'' (1996)\n\nSources:<ref name=\"one\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0796196/ |title=Josephine Siao |accessdate=15 April 2010 |publisher=imdb.com}}</ref><ref name=\"two\">{{Cite web |url=http://chinesemov.com/actors/Josephine%20Siao.html |title=Josephine Siao |accessdate=15 April 2010 |publisher=chinesemov.com}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n* \u6d0b\u76f8 : \u82f1\u7f8e\u793e\u4ea4\u79ae\u5100\n\n==Siao Fong-fong Performing Art Hall ==\nThe Siao Fong-fong Performing Art Hall was established in 1998 at [[Shantang Street]] of [[Luzhi]] township in the Siao family's former residence.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0796196}}\n* [http://www.cinemasie.com/fiche/personne/josephinesiao/fiche.html Siao Fong Fong movies at cinemasie.com]\n* [http://ecsaf.org.hk End Child Sexual Abuse Foundation (founded and chaired by Siao)]\n\n{{s-start}} {{s-ach}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1988<br>'''for ''The Wrong Couples'' '''\n| before= [[Sylvia Chang]]<br>for ''Passion''\n| after = [[Anita Mui]]<br>for ''[[Rouge (film)|Rouge]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]\n| years = 1995<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''\n| before= [[Crissy Rock]]<br>for ''[[Ladybird, Ladybird]]''\n| after = [[Anouk Grinberg]]<br>for ''[[Mon Homme (film)|Mon Homme]]''\n}} \n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Critics Society Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1995<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''<br>share with [[Siqin Gaowa]]\n| before= [[Joan Chen]]<br>for ''[[Red Rose, White Rose]]''\n| after = [[Maggie Cheung]]<br>for ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1996<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''\n| before= [[Anita Yuen]]<br>for ''[[He's a Woman, She's a Man]]''\n| after = [[Maggie Cheung]]<br>for ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Golden Bauhinia Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1996<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''\n| before= None\n| after = [[Maggie Cheung]]<br>for ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] Life Achievement Award\n| years = 2009\n| before= [[Raymond Chow]]\n| after = [[Lau Kar-leung]]\n}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = Awards for Josephine Siao\n|list =\n{{GoldenBellAwardBestActress}}\n{{GoldenHorseAwardBestActress 1981-2000}}\n{{GoldenHorseAwardBestSupportingActress}}\n{{Best Actress HKFA}}\n{{Best Actress HKFCSA}}\n{{Silver Bear for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Siao, Josephine}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Cantopop singers]]\n[[Category:Child psychologists]]\n[[Category:Chinese Civil War refugees]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong female singers]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong film actresses]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong psychologists]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong television actresses]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong women writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Regis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Seton Hall University alumni]]\n[[Category:Silver Bear for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:Chinese film actresses]]\n[[Category:Chinese television actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century Hong Kong actresses]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong people of Shanghainese descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{infobox person\n| name = Josephine Siao\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| native_name        = \u856d\u82b3\u82b3\n| native_name_lang   = zh\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_name = Siao Loeng (\u856d\u4eae)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|3|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Shanghai]], China\n| nationality = Australia| alma_mater = [[Seton Hall University]]<br>[[Regis University]]\n| occupation = Actress, television personality\n| years_active = 1954\u20131997\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Charlie Chin]]|1976|1978|reason=div}}<br>{{marriage|Clarence Chang|1980}}\n| children = Chang Hoi-kam (daughter)<br>Chang Nga-kam (daughter)\n| parents = Xiao Naizhen (father)<br>Cheng Fenghui (mother)\n| awards = {{Awards|award=Best Child Actor|year=1955|title=The Orphan Girl|role=Mui Kit (childhood)|name=[[Asia-Pacific Film Festival]]}}{{Awards|award=[[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]|year=1996|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun|name=[[Berlin International Film Festival]]}}{{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1996|title=Hu-Du-Men|role=Lang Kim-sum|name=Asia-Pacific Film Festival}}<br>{{awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]|year=1988|title=[[The Wrong Couples]]|role=Wong Mui|year2=1996|title2=[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]|role2=May Sun}}{{Awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Award for Lifetime Achievement|Lifetime Achievement Award]]|year=2009}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Bauhinia Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1996|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun}}}}{{awards|award=[[Hong Kong Film Critics Society Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Best Actress|year=1995|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun}}}}{{awards|award=[[Asian Film Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=Outstanding Contribution to Asian Cinema|year=2007}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Horse Film Festival and Awards|Golden Horse Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Golden Horse Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]|year=1975|title=Girl Friend|role=Meng Ya-ping}}{{Awards|award=[[Golden Horse Award for Best Leading Actress|Best Leading Actress]]|year=1995|title=Summer Snow|role=May Sun|year2=1996|title2=[[Hu-Du-Men]]|role2=Lang Kim-sum}}}}{{awards|award=[[Golden Bell Awards]]|name={{Awards|award=[[Golden Bell Award for Best Actress|Best Actress]]|year=1995|title=Autumn Water & Vast Sky|role=Hsiang I-hung}}}}\n| module = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n| t = \u856d\u82b3\u82b3\n| s = \u8427\u82b3\u82b3\n| p = Xi\u0101o F\u0101ngf\u0101ng\n| j = siu1 fong1 fong1\n}}\n| module2 = {{infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| alias = Sister Fong-fong (\u82b3\u82b3\u59d0)\n | background = temporary\n| origin = [[British Hong Kong]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Josephine Siao Fong-fong''' {{post-nominals|MBE}} ({{Lang-zh|s=\u8427\u82b3\u82b3|t=\u856d\u82b3\u82b3|p=Xi\u0101o F\u0101ngf\u0101ng|j=siu1 fong1 fong1}}) is a Hong Kong film star who became popular as a child actress and continued her success as a mature actress, winning numerous awards including Best Actress at the [[45th Berlin International Film Festival]] (for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'').<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=https://www.berlinale.de/en/archive/jahresarchive/1995/03_preistraeger_1995/03_preistraeger_1995.html |title=Berlinale: 1995 Prize Winners |accessdate=1 January 2012 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref> Since retiring from show business (partly due to her increasing deafness), she has become a writer and a psychologist, known for her work against child abuse.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Avenue of Stars Siao Fong Fong.JPG|right|thumb|Hand prints of Siao Fong-fong on the [[Avenue of Stars, Hong Kong]]]]\nJosephine Siao Fong-fong was born as Siao Liang in [[Shanghai]], with her ancestral home in [[Luzhi]], [[Suzhou]], Jiangsu. At the age of two, she was brought to Hong Kong by her parents.\n\nSiao's first movie appearance was at age six, and she became one of the biggest teen idols in Hong Kong during the late 1960s, along with frequent co-star [[Connie Chan Po-chu]]. The two were often cast in [[wuxia]] films as disciples of the same master and sometimes\u2014when Connie played the male lead\u2014as young heroes in love. Back in the 1960s, Josephine's and Connie's fans maintained a heated rivalry. News of their fans getting into catfights was not uncommon in those days.\n\nUnlike many child stars, Siao made a successful transition to adult stardom, remaining one of Hong Kong's most prolific and popular actresses.  She was also one of the directors (co-directing with Leung Po-Chih \u6881\u666e\u667a) and writers of ''[[Jumping Ash]]'' (\u8df3\u7070). This film is regarded as a prelude to the [[Hong Kong New Wave]] in the 1980s by film critics.\n\nHaving largely missed out on formal education because of her acting career as a child, Siao pursued her studies in later years despite the handicap of increasing deafness and the demands of raising a family (she has two daughters by her second husband).  During this time she made fewer films, but her output included highly praised work such as her award-winning performance in ''Summer Snow'' (1995) as a middle-aged widow trying to cope with her father-in-law suffering from Alzheimer's Disease.\n\nWestern fans of [[martial arts film]]s will probably know her best from the [[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|''Fong Sai-yuk'' films]] made in 1993, in which she played [[Jet Li]]'s [[kung fu]]\u2013fighting mother. (These films were released on Western DVD as ''The Legend''.)\n\nSiao has been retired from show business since 1997 in favour of her work in child psychology.  In particular, she is a noted campaigner against child abuse, and founded the End Child Sexual Abuse Foundation, which she now chairs, in 1999.  She is also a published author.\n\nSome of the milestones in her life include:\n* 1970: Bachelor's degree in Mass Communications and Asian Studies at [[Seton Hall University]]\n* 1974: won the best actress award at Spain Film Festival and Taiwan Film Festival\n* 1990: obtained a master's degree in child psychology from [[Regis University]]\n* 1995: won the best actress award at the Berlin Film Festival for ''Summer Snow''\n* 1996: member of the Most Excellent [[Order of the British Empire]]\n* 2009: Life Achievement Award of the [[28th Hong Kong Film Awards]]\n\n== Selective filmography ==\n* ''[[An Orphan's Tragedy]]'' (1955)\n* ''[[Rhythm of the Wave]]'' (1974)\n* ''[[Jumping Ash]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[Lam Au Chun]]'' (1978)\n* ''[[The Spooky Bunch]]'' (1980)\n* ''[[Plain Jane to the Rescue]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[The Perfect Match (1982 film)|The Perfect Match]]'' (1982)\n* ''[[A Friend from Inner Space]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[The Wrong Couples]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[Fist of Fury 1991]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Fist of Fury 1991 II]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Too Happy for Words]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Fong Sai-yuk (film)|Fong Sai Yuk]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Fong Sai-yuk II]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Always on My Mind]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Kin Chan No Cinema Jack]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Hu-Du-Men]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[Mahjong Dragon]]'' (1996)\n\nSources:<ref name=\"one\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0796196/ |title=Josephine Siao |accessdate=15 April 2010 |publisher=imdb.com}}</ref><ref name=\"two\">{{Cite web |url=http://chinesemov.com/actors/Josephine%20Siao.html |title=Josephine Siao |accessdate=15 April 2010 |publisher=chinesemov.com}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n* \u6d0b\u76f8 : \u82f1\u7f8e\u793e\u4ea4\u79ae\u5100\n\n==Siao Fong-fong Performing Art Hall ==\nThe Siao Fong-fong Performing Art Hall was established in 1998 at [[Shantang Street]] of [[Luzhi]] township in the Siao family's former residence.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0796196}}\n* [http://www.cinemasie.com/fiche/personne/josephinesiao/fiche.html Siao Fong Fong movies at cinemasie.com]\n* [http://ecsaf.org.hk End Child Sexual Abuse Foundation (founded and chaired by Siao)]\n\n{{s-start}} {{s-ach}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1988<br>'''for ''The Wrong Couples'' '''\n| before= [[Sylvia Chang]]<br>for ''Passion''\n| after = [[Anita Mui]]<br>for ''[[Rouge (film)|Rouge]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Silver Bear for Best Actress]]\n| years = 1995<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''\n| before= [[Crissy Rock]]<br>for ''[[Ladybird, Ladybird]]''\n| after = [[Anouk Grinberg]]<br>for ''[[Mon Homme (film)|Mon Homme]]''\n}} \n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Critics Society Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1995<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''<br>share with [[Siqin Gaowa]]\n| before= [[Joan Chen]]<br>for ''[[Red Rose, White Rose]]''\n| after = [[Maggie Cheung]]<br>for ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Hong Kong Film Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1996<br>'''for ''[[Summer Snow (film)|Summer Snow]]'' '''\n| before= [[Anita Yuen]]<br>for ''[[He's a Woman, She's a Man]]''\n| after = [[Maggie Cheung]]<br>for ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]''\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title = [[Golden Bauhinia Awards]] for Best Actress\n| years = 1996<br>