d for Best Performance by a Younger Actor in a Television Series|Best Performance by a Younger Actor in a Television Series]] || [[Max Charles]] || {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Directors Guild of Canada]] Awards || Best Sound Editing \u2013 Television Series || John Loranger, Dan Sexton, Adam Stein, Nathan Robitaille, Jill Purdy, Richard Calistan, Joe Mancuso, Craig MacLellan (for \"Night Train\") || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=2016 Directors Guild Of Canada Awards Nominees Announced|url=http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/2016-directors-guild-of-canada-awards-nominees-announced-584005731.html|publisher=Newswire|date=June 22, 2016|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Fangoria Chainsaw Awards]] || Best TV Makeup/Creature FX || Steve Newburn, Sean Sansom || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=Never mind Oscar, here's the 2016 FANGORIA Chainsaw Awards Nominees Ballot!|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/never-mind-oscar-heres-the-2016-fangoria-chainsaw-awards-nominees-ballot/|work=Fangoria|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Golden Maple Awards]] || Best Actress in a TV Series Broadcast in the US || [[Natalie Brown (actress)|Natalie Brown]] || {{won}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=ACISE-LA announces 2016 Golden Maple Awards winners|url=http://www.tv-eh.com/2016/07/01/acise-la-announces-2016-golden-maple-awards-winners/|website=TV, eh?|first=Greg|last=David|accessdate=April 9, 2017|date=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Visual Effects Society Awards]] || Outstanding Visual Effects in a Photoreal Episode || Dennis Berardi, Luke Groves, Matt Glover, Trey Harrell, Warren Appleby (for \"Identity\") || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=14th Annual VES Awards Nominees|url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/14th-annual-ves-awards-nominees|publisher=Visual Effects Society|accessdate=April 9, 2017|date=January 12, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || [[43rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]] || Best Performance by a Younger Actor in a Television Series || Max Charles || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title='Rogue One,' 'Walking Dead' Lead Saturn Awards Nominations|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/saturn-awards-nominations-2017-rogue-one-walking-dead-1202000833/|work=Variety|accessdate=April 9, 2017|date=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2018 \n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[44th Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]|| Best Horror Television Series || ''The Strain'' || {{nom}} || rowspan=2| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|title=\u2018Black Panther,\u2019 \u2018Walking Dead\u2019 Rule Saturn Awards Nominations|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 15, 2018|accessdate=March 15, 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6xwc1azco?url=http://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/|archivedate=March 15, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Performance by a Younger Actor in a Television Series || Max Charles || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n=== Ratings ===\n{{main|List of The Strain episodes#Ratings}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of vampire television series]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|The Strain (TV series)}}\n* {{IMDb title|2654620}}\n\n{{Guillermo del Toro}}\n{{FX network programming}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strain, The}}\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2017 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American horror television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:FX Networks original programming]]\n[[Category:Nonlinear narrative television series]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on American novels]]\n[[Category:Television series about viral outbreaks]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Undead in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Vampires in television]]\n[[Category:Works by Guillermo del Toro]]\n[[Category:The Holocaust in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = The Strain\n| image                = The Strain 2014 Intertitle.jpg\n| caption              = Title card from seasons 1\u20132\n| genre                = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Vampire literature|Vampire]] [[Horror fiction|horror]]\n*[[Drama]]}}\n| creator              = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Guillermo del Toro]]\n* [[Chuck Hogan]]\n}}\n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[The Strain]]''|Guillermo del Toro<br />Chuck Hogan}}\n| starring             = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Corey Stoll]]\n* [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]]\n* [[M\u00eda Maestro]]\n* [[Kevin Durand]]\n* [[Jonathan Hyde]]\n* [[Richard Sammel]]\n* [[Sean Astin]]\n* [[Jack Kesy]]\n* [[Natalie Brown (actress)|Natalie Brown]]\n* [[Miguel Gomez (actor)|Miguel Gomez]]\n* Ben Hyland\n* [[Max Charles]]\n* [[Ruta Gedmintas]]\n* [[Rupert Penry-Jones]]\n* [[Samantha Mathis]]\n* [[Joaquin Cosio]]\n}}\n| voices               = [[Robin Atkin Downes]]\n| theme_music_composer =\n| opentheme            =\n| endtheme             =\n| composer             = [[Ramin Djawadi]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 4 <!-- Refers to the number of seasons that have aired. Only update after a new season begins. -->\n| num_episodes         = 46 <!-- Refers to the number of episodes that have been broadcast. Only update after a new episode airs. -->\n| list_episodes        = List of The Strain episodes\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist |\n* Guillermo del Toro\n* [[Carlton Cuse]]\n* Chuck Hogan\n* Gary Ungar\n* [[J. Miles Dale]]\n* [[David Weddle]]\n* [[Bradley Thompson]]\n* [[Regina Corrado]]\n}}\n| producer             = \n| location             = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]\n| cinematography       = {{Plainlist|\n*Checco Verese\n*Gabriel Beristain\n*[[Miroslaw Baszak]]}}\n| editor               = {{Plainlist|\n*Kathryn Himoff\n*Christopher Nelson\n*Sarah Boyd}}\n| camera               =\n| runtime              = {{Plainlist|\n* 39\u201344 minutes (regular)\n* 70 minutes (pilot)}}\n|company = {{Plainlist|\n* Double Dare You\n* Carlton Cuse Productions (2014\u201315)\n* Cuse Productions (2016\u201317)\n* FX Productions (2014\u201315)\n* FXP (2016\u201317)\n}}\n| distributor          = [[20th Television]]\n| picture_format       =\n| audio_format         =\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2014|7|13}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2017|9|17}}\n| website              = \n| channel              = [[FX (TV channel)|FX]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Strain''''' is an American [[horror fiction|horror]] [[drama]] television series that aired on [[FX (TV channel)|FX]] from July 13, 2014, to September 17, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fx-orders-guillermo-del-toros-657628|title=FX Orders Guillermo del Toro's 'The Strain' to Series|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|last2=O'Connell|first2=Michael|date=November 19, 2013|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref> It was created by [[Guillermo del Toro]] and [[Chuck Hogan]], based on their [[The Strain|novel trilogy of the same name]]. [[Carlton Cuse]] serves as executive producer and showrunner. Del Toro and Hogan wrote the pilot episode, \"[[Night Zero (The Strain)|Night Zero]]\", which del Toro directed. A thirteen-episode first season was ordered on November 19, 2013.<ref name=\"series\"/> The pilot episode premiered at the [[ATX Television Festival]] in [[Austin, Texas]], in early June 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/04/15/guillermo-del-toro-fx-the-strain-atx-television-festival/ |title=Guillermo Del Toro's FX series 'The Strain' to have world premiere at ATX Television Festival{{nbsp}}\u2014 EXCLUSIVE |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=Karen |last=Valby |date=April 15, 2014 |accessdate=July 6, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 6, 2014, FX renewed ''The Strain'' for a 13-episode second season which premiered on July 12, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bibel|first=Sara|title='The Strain' Renewed for Thirteen-Episode Season Two by FX|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/08/19/the-strain-renewed-for-season-two-by-fx/294611/|accessdate=August 19, 2014|publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]]|date=August 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"S2 Premiere\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2015/05/the-strain-season-2-july-premiere-fx-1201429801/ |title='The Strain' Season 2 Gets July Premiere Date On FX |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Denise |last=Petski |date=May 19, 2015 |accessdate=May 19, 2015}}</ref> On August 7, 2015, FX renewed ''The Strain'' for a 10-episode third season which premiered on August 28, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/the-strain-season-3-american-horror-story-hotel-oct-7-1201559078/ |title=FX Renews 'The Strain,' Sets Premiere Dates for 'AHS: Hotel' and More |work=Variety |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"10 episodes\">{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2015/10/06/the-strain-season-3-nora-dead-quinlan-eldritch/ |title=''Strain'' EPs Clear the Air on Nora's Fate, Tease a 'Different, Faster' Season 3 |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=October 6, 2015 |accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/05/10/youre-the-worst-season-3-premiere-date-the-strain-returns-fx/ |title=You're the Worst, The Strain Get Summer Return Dates at FX Networks |publisher=TVLine |first=Rebecca |last=Iannucci |date=May 10, 2016 |accessdate=May 10, 2016}}</ref> FX renewed the series for a fourth and final season on September 27, 2016,<ref name=\"final season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/strain-renewed-fourth-final-season-932948|title='The Strain' Renewed for Fourth and Final Season at FX|work=The Hollywood Reporter|first=Lesley|last=Goldberg|date=September 27, 2016|accessdate=September 27, 2016}}</ref> which premiered on July 16, 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/05/09/the-strain-final-season-4-premiere-date-fx/|title=The Strain's Fourth and Final Season Gets Premiere Date on FX|publisher=TVLine|first=Dave|last=Nemetz|date=May 9, 2017|accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> {{Aired episodes|num=46|title=The Strain|finished=all|seasons=4}}\n\nThe show centers around Dr. Ephraim Goodweather, the head of the CDC's New York-based Canary Project, who is called upon to investigate an airplane landing wherein everyone aboard is dead. What his team discovers is a viral outbreak that has similarities to an ancient strain of vampirism. The virus begins to spread and Goodweather works with his team and a group of the city's residents to wage a war to save humanity.\n\n== Cast and characters ==\n\n=== Main cast ===\n* [[Corey Stoll]] as Dr. Ephraim \"Eph\" Goodweather, the head of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] Canary Team in New York City.<ref name=\"Stoll\"/>\n* [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] as Professor Abraham Setrakian, a [[Holocaust]] survivor turned New York [[pawnbroker]]. Jim Watson portrays a young Setrakian in [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]].<ref name=\"bradley\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fxs-strain-casts-david-bradley-658804|title=FX's 'The Strain' Casts 'Harry Potter's' David Bradley to Replace John Hurt|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Ng|first=Philiana|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=November 22, 2013}}</ref><ref name=globalnews>{{cite news |title=Actors Brown and Watson talk vampire thriller \"The Strain\" |url=http://globalnews.ca/video/1623990/actors-brown-and-watson-talk-vampire-thriller-the-strain |publisher=[[Global News]] |date=October 20, 2014 |accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[M\u00eda Maestro]] as Dr. Nora Martinez, a member of the CDC Canary Team and Eph's closest ally<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/guillermo-del-toro-the-strain-mia-maestro/|title=FX Pilots: Director Ang Lee Departs Drama TYRANT, While Guillermo del Toro's THE STRAIN Finds Its Female Lead in Mia Maestro|publisher=Collider|last=Trumbore|first=Dave|date=May 20, 2013|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132).\n* [[Kevin Durand]] as Vasiliy Fet, a once-solitary rat exterminator of [[Ukrainian Americans|Ukrainian descent]], who is caught up in the fight for humanity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2013/tv/news/strain-1200416803/|title=Durand joins Stoll in FX's 'Strain'|last=Weisman|first=Jon|work=Variety|date=April 26, 2013|accessdate=April 27, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Jonathan Hyde]] as Eldritch Palmer/The Master, an elderly billionaire invalid driven to obtain immortality. Charlie Gallant portrays a young Palmer in flashbacks.<ref name=\"hydesammel\"/>\n* [[Richard Sammel]] as Thomas Eichhorst, an undead vampire acolyte of the Master who has a 70-year history with Setrakian. In his former life, he was a [[Nazism|Nazi]] commander at the [[Treblinka extermination camp]] in [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|German-occupied]] [[General Government|Poland]].<ref name=\"hydesammel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/guillermo-del-toros-fx-pilot-526231|title=Guillermo del Toro's FX Pilot 'The Strain' Adds Pair to Cast (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=May 21, 2013|accessdate=May 22, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Sean Astin]] as Jim Kent, a CDC administrator who works with Eph and Nora<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/07/09/sean-astin-fx-vampire-drama/|title=Sean Astin joins FX vampire drama|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Hibberd|first=James|date=July 9, 2013|accessdate=July 10, 2013}}</ref> (season 1, guest season 2).\n* [[Jack Kesy]] as Gabriel Bolivar/The Master, a philandering rock star with an appetite for recreational drugs and is one of the Master's vampire acolytes before becoming the Master's host body (seasons 1\u20132, recurring season 3).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/06/cable-pilots-the-leftovers-quarry-the-strain-add-to-casts/|title=Cable Pilots 'The Leftovers', 'Quarry' & 'The Strain' Add To Casts|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=June 21, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Natalie Brown (actress)|Natalie Brown]] as Kelly Goodweather, Eph's estranged wife<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/09/pilots-line-of-sight-strain-add-regulars/|title=Pilots 'Line Of Sight' & 'Strain' Add Regulars|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=September 3, 2013|accessdate=September 4, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20133, recurring season 4).\n* [[Miguel Gomez (actor)|Miguel Gomez]] as Augustin \"Gus\" Elizalde, a gang member who just got out of juvenile prison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/06/miguel-gomez-joins-fx-pilot-the-strain-roger-howarth-to-recur-on-californication/|title=Miguel Gomez Joins FX Pilot 'The Strain', Roger Howarth To Recur On 'Californication'|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=June 11, 2013|accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>\n* Ben Hyland (season 1) and [[Max Charles]] (seasons 2\u20134) as Zach Goodweather, the son of Ephraim and Kelly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theislandnow.com/news-98/munsey-park-boy-getting-taste-of-hollywood-life/|title=Munsey Park boy getting taste of Hollywood life|work=The Island Now|last=San Antonio|first=Bill|date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"zach recast\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2015/01/max-charles-the-strain-recasting-fx-1201343303/|title=Max Charles Joins 'The Strain' As Regular In Recasting|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=January 7, 2015|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Robin Atkin Downes]] as the voice of the Master, one of the seven Ancient vampires and the series' central antagonist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.comicbooked.com/strain-exclusive-interview-robin-atkin-downes/|title=The Strain: Exclusive Interview with Robin Atkin Downes|work=Comic Booked|last=Clutter|first=Aaron|date=July 16, 2014|accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Ruta Gedmintas]] as Dutch Velders, an internet hacker hired by Palmer, who turns against the company when she realizes what she has done (recurring season 1, main seasons 2\u20134).\n* [[Rupert Penry-Jones]] as Mr. Quinlan, a half-vampire with a vendetta against the Master<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/08/strain-recap-season-2-episode-5.html|title=The Strain Recap: Rest in Hairpiece|publisher=Vulture|first=Kenny|last=Herzog|date=August 9, 2015|accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref> (seasons 2\u20134).\n* [[Samantha Mathis]] as Justine Feraldo, a tenacious New York City councilwoman for [[Staten Island]] (recurring season 2, main season 3).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Petski|first1=Denise|title=Samantha Mathis Cast in 'The Strain; Inbar Lavi in 'The Last Ship'|url=http://deadline.com/2014/11/samantha-mathis-joins-the-strain-inbar-lavi-in-the-last-ship-1201284535/|publisher=Deadline.com|date=November 14, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Joaqu\u00edn Cos\u00edo]] as Angel Guzman Hurtado, a retired wrestler once known as \"The Silver Angel\" (recurring season 2, main season 3).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-fien-print/exclusive-fxs-the-strain-finds-its-vampire-fighting-silver-angel |title=Exclusive: FX's 'The Strain' finds its vampire-fighting Silver Angel |publisher=HitFix |first=Daniel |last=Fienberg |date=January 13, 2015 |accessdate=January 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Recurring cast ===\n* [[Cas Anvar]] as Sanjay Desai, a Stoneheart employee and subordinate of Eichhorst (seasons 3\u20134).\n* [[Pedro Miguel Arce]] as Felix, Gus's friend (season 1).\n* [[Adriana Barraza]] as Guadalupe Elizalde, Gus and Crispin's mother (seasons 1\u20133).\n* Brenda Bazinet as Pauline McGeever, a vampire victim experimented on by Eph and Nora (season 2).\n* [[Nigel Bennett]] as Dr. Werner Dreverhaven, a former Nazi physician turned vampire (seasons 2\u20133).\n* Anne Betancourt as Mariela Martinez, Nora's mother who suffers from [[dementia]] (season 1).\n* [[Lizzie Brocher\u00e9]] as Coco Marchand, Palmer's new personal assistant (season 2).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tracking-board.com/lizzie-brochere-to-help-track-down-fxs-the-strain/ |title=Lizzie Brochere to help track down FX's 'The Strain'|publisher=The Tracking Board|first=Maggie |last=Loyal |date=November 13, 2014 |accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Inga Cadranel]] as Diane, a [[Queens]] native and Kelly's best friend (season 1).\n* [[Ron Canada]] as George Lyle, the [[Mayor of New York City]] (season 2).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Barton|first1=Steve|title=The Strain Season 2 \u2013 Ron Canada Manages NYC Crisis as Mayor|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/79898/strain-season-2-ron-canada-manages-nyc-crisis-mayor/|publisher=Dread Central|date=November 24, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Francis Capra]] as Crispin Elizalde, Gus's con artist brother (season 1).<ref name=\"Deadline-Maillet\"/>\n* [[K. C. Collins]] as Captain Daniel Roman, an [[United States Army|Army]] officer who formerly served at a nuclear [[Missile launch facility|missile silo]] (season 4).\n* [[Nicola Correia-Damude]] as Nikki Taylor, a roommate and once girlfriend of Dutch Velders (seasons 1\u20132).\n* [[Roger Cross]] as Reggie Fitzwilliam, Palmer's caregiver and head of security (seasons 1\u20132).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/07/nicole-ari-parker-to-recur-on-revolution/|title=Nicole Ari Parker To Recur On ''Revolution'', Roger Cross Joins FX Pilot ''The Strain''|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=July 24, 2013|accessdate=July 25, 2013}}</ref>\n* Miranda Edwards as Eve, a human agent working with Quinlan and The Ancients (season 2).\n* [[Kevin Hanchard]] as Curtis Fitzwilliam, a firefighter and Reggie's brother (season 2).<ref>{{cite web|last=Otero|first=Harry A.|title=The Strain Season 2 Episode 3 Review: Fort Defiance|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/07/the-strain-season-2-episode-3-review-fort-defiance/|publisher=TV Fanatic|date=July 26, 2015|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Jamie Hector]] as Alonso Creem, an arms dealer and gang leader (seasons 1\u20132, 4).\n* [[Leslie Hope]] as Joan Luss, an attorney and one of the plane's surviving passengers (season 1).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2013/08/12/the-strain-leslie-hope-fx/|title=Exclusive: ''24''{{'}}s Leslie Hope Battles FX's ''Strain''|publisher=TVLine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=August 12, 2013|accessdate=August 13, 2013}}</ref>\n* Jocelyn Hudon as Abby, a maid who befriends Zach (season 4).\n* [[Doug Jones (actor)|Doug Jones]] as one of the Ancients, the seven original vampires.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/2015/06/05/doug-jones-talks-falling-skies-the-strain-crimson-peak-hellboy-3/|title=Doug Jones Talks Falling Skies, The Strain, Crimson Peak, & Hellboy 3|last=Davis|first=Brandon|publisher=comicbook.com|date=June 5, 2015|accessdate=July 13, 2015}}</ref> Jones also portrays the Master's previous host before Jusef in a flashback (seasons 1\u20133).\n* [[Daniel Kash]] as Dr. Everett Barnes, the director of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] and later [[United States Secretary of Health and Human Services|Secretary for Health and Human Services]] (seasons 1\u20132).\n* Parveen Kaur as Aanya Gupta, a waitress and the daughter of the owners of the Tandoori Palace (season 2).\n* Tom Kemp as Cardinal McNamara, a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] cardinal who is selling an item of interest to both Setrakian and Palmer (season 2).\n* [[Regina King]] as Ruby Wain, Bolivar's intelligent and accomplished manager (season 1).<ref name=\"Dec5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/12/regina-king-the-strain-fx/|title=Regina King Joins FX Series ''The Strain''|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|publisher=Deadline.com|date=December 5, 2013|accessdate=December 6, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Ron Lea]] as Harrison McGeever, a vampire victim experimented on by Eph and Nora (season 2).\n* [[Robert Maillet]] as Jusef Sardu, a 19th-century [[Poles|Polish]] [[Polish nobility|noble]] who was the Master's host body until he was gravely injured<ref name=\"Deadline-Maillet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/07/guillermo-del-toro-sets-pacific-rims-robert-maillet-as-main-strain-villain/|title=Guillermo del Toro Sets 'Pacific Rim's' Robert Maillet As Main 'Strain' Villain|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Patten|first=Dominic|date=July 10, 2013|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132, 4).\n* [[Stephen McHattie]] as Vaun, leader of a band of undead hunters sent to destroy the vampire outbreak (seasons 1\u20132).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/07/27/the-strain-fort-defiance-review |title=The Strain: \"Fort Defiance\" Review |publisher=IGN |first=Jesse |last=Schedeen |date=July 26, 2015 |accessdate=July 27, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Melanie Merkosky]] as Sylvia Kent, Jim Kent's cancer-stricken wife (season 1).<ref name=\"Dec5\"/>\n* [[Rhona Mitra]] as Charlotte, a woman who joins Fet and Quinlan in their search for weapons to destroy the Master (season 4).\n* [[Drew Nelson (actor)|Drew Nelson]] as Matt Sayles, Kelly Goodweather's live-in boyfriend (season 1).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/drewnelsonlive/status/443208036996243456 |title=Twitter / drewnelsonlive: @MiEg007 I have a major recurring |publisher=Twitter |date=March 10, 2014 |accessdate=May 17, 2014}}</ref>\n* Paulino Nunes as Captain Frank Kowalski, an [[New York City Police Department|NYPD]] officer working with Justine Feraldo (season 2\u20133).\n* [[America Olivo]] as Captain Kate Rogers, the commander of a squad of NYPD combatants (season 3).\n* [[Angel Parker]] as Alex Green, the leader of a group of anti-strigoi resistance fighters (season 4).\n* [[Jonathan Potts]] as Captain Doyle Redfern, pilot of the flight and one of the outbreak's few survivors (season 1).\n* [[Michael Reventar]] as Raul, Gus's cousin (season 4).\n* [[Kim Roberts (actress)|Kim Roberts]] as Neeva, Joan Luss' nanny and housekeeper (season 1).\n* Nikolai Witschl as Ansel Barbour, one of the plane's surviving passengers (season 1).\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\n[[File:The Strain promotional poster.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Promotional poster which was withdrawn from circulation after a number of complaints.<ref name=\"poster\"/>]]\nIn 2006, del Toro pitched ''The Strain'' as a television series, but negotiations broke down when the network president at [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] asked him to make it a comedy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenrant.com/guillermo-del-toro-talks-future-projects-ross-10001/|title=Guillermo del Toro Talks Future Projects & More|last=Miller|first=Ross|publisher=Screen Rant|date=2009|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> An agent suggested expanding the concept as a novel series instead.<ref name=\"Deadline\">{{cite web|title='The Strain' Drama From Guillermo Del Toro And Carlton Cuse Gets Pilot Order At FX|url=http://www.deadline.com/2012/09/the-strain-drama-from-guillermo-del-toro-and-carlton-cuse-gets-pilot-order-at-fx/|publisher=Deadline.com|author1=Andreeva, Nellie |author2=Fleming Jr., Mike |date=September 20, 2012|accessdate=February 19, 2013}}</ref> Del Toro asked Chuck Hogan to co-write the series, explaining: \"I've written short stories in Spanish and English. I've written screenplays. But I'm not good at forensic novels. I'm not good at hazmat language and that CSI-style precision. When [[Bram Stoker|Stoker]] wrote ''[[Dracula]]'', it was very modern, a ''[[CSI (franchise)|CSI]]'' sort of novel. I wanted to give ''The Strain'' a procedural feel, where everything seems real.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archive.wired.com/entertainment/hollywood/magazine/17-06/mf_deltoro|title=Q&A: Hobbit Director Guillermo del Toro on the Future of Film|last=Brown|first=Scott|work=Wired|date=May 22, 2009|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> Hogan agreed after reading a page and a half of del Toro's 12-page project outline; the duo collaborated for the first year on a handshake, with no contract or publishing deal in place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sarahweinman.com/confessions/2009/06/chuck-hogan-on-the-strain-and-collaborative-writing.html|title=Chuck Hogan on Co-Writing THE STRAIN with \"Some Other Guy\"|last=Weinman|first=Sarah|publisher=Sarahweinman.com|date=June 2, 2009|accessdate=June 28, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502201818/http://www.sarahweinman.com/confessions/2009/06/chuck-hogan-on-the-strain-and-collaborative-writing.html|archivedate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The first installment, ''[[The Strain]]'', was released in 2009. It was followed by 2010's ''[[The Fall (del Toro / Hogan novel)|The Fall]]'' and 2011's ''[[The Night Eternal]]''.\n\nAfter the first book's publication, studios and networks began making offers for the film and television adaptation rights, but del Toro and Hogan declined, not wanting a screen version to influence the way they were writing the books. After the third book's publication, the authors talked with every cable network that had expressed interest. FX was deemed most suitable because they wanted to follow the books closely and liked the idea of ''The Strain'' as a close-ended series consisting of three to five seasons. Del Toro stated that the first two novels can be covered by one season each, while ''The Night Eternal'' may be split into two or three seasons. The author is also open to creative detours that may develop as the series goes on, possibly incorporating material cut from the books. Del Toro intends to direct as many episodes as his busy schedule allows.<ref name=\"Deadline\"/> Before the series order was announced, FX gave the writing team the go-ahead to script another ten episodes, which del Toro rewrote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/174729-exclusive-guillermo-del-toro-on-the-televised-horrors-of-the-strain-fx-orders-scripts-for-entire-season|title=Exclusive: Guillermo del Toro on the Televised Horrors of ''The Strain'', FX Orders Scripts for Entire Season|last=Turek|first=Ryan|publisher=Shock Till You Drop|date=June 30, 2013|accessdate=June 30, 2013}}</ref> FX president [[John Landgraf]] has stated that the series will consist of \"39\u201365 episodes, no less, no more\", adding \"What if a television show could be just the length that is optimal for that story?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/08/tca-fxs-john-landgraf-signals-end-of-nuclear-arms-race-of-darkness-talks-the-strain-game-plan-fx-brand-expansion/|title=TCA: FX's John Landgraf Signals End Of 'Nuclear Arms Race Of Darkness', Talks ''The Strain'' Game Plan, FX Brand Expansion|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|publisher=Deadline.com|date=August 2, 2013|accessdate=August 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the style of the show's production, del Toro stated: \"Basically I'm trying to do what I do in my movies which is to show it as a reality, but as a reality that is stylized. It's not like ''CSI'' or ''[[The Wire]]'', it's real but it feels a little stylized. But the way the camera work will be is very realistic. We want to keep the camera very documentary even if the look of the show is not. The look of the show is very designed. The style of the camera and the storytelling will be very loose. It will evolve from that feel of reality, and little by little we want to evolve into more stylish, horror feel that requires smoother camera moves, more suspense and atmosphere-driven moments so it will be a mixture. I don't think that mixture has been seen a lot on TV.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geek-news.mtv.com/2012/11/12/interview-guillermo-del-toro-the-strain/|title=Interview: Guillermo del Toro Takes 'The Strain' To Dark Horse And Beyond|last=Wright|first=Eddie|publisher=MTV|date=November 12, 2012|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFX ordered a thirteen-episode first season for the series on November 19, 2013, and announced that the series would premiere in July 2014.<ref name=\"series\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2013/11/19/the-strain-fx-series-order/|title='The Strain' gets FX series order: More vamps!|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Hibberd|first=James|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref> In August 2015, del Toro and Cuse announced a five-season plan for the series after the third season renewal, Cuse said, \"From the very beginning, we had really talked about the first book being the first season, the second book being the next two seasons and the third book the last two seasons\". He also said that beyond the first and second seasons, which are 13 episodes each, the remaining seasons were planned to each consist of 10 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2015/08/07/the-strain-guillermo-del-toro-carlton-cuse|title=Guillermo del Toro and Carlton Cuse lay out five-year plan for ''The Strain''|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Robinson|first=Will|date=August 7, 2015|accessdate=August 8, 2015}}</ref> However, in September 2016, FX announced the series' fourth season would be its last. Cuse stated, \"After finishing the writing on season three, Guillermo, Chuck and I looked at our remaining story and felt the best version could be told in one more season.\"<ref name=\"final season\"/>\n\n=== Casting ===\nDel Toro and Cuse cast the series together.<ref name=\"HitFix1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/the-fien-print/guillermo-del-toro-brings-the-strain-to-comic-con-live-blog|title=Guillermo del Toro Brings ''The Strain'' to Comic-Con: Live-Blog|last=Fienberg|first=Daniel|work=[[HitFix]]|date=July 27, 2014|accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref> Stoll was cast as Eph Goodweather based on his performance in ''[[Midnight in Paris]]''.<ref name=\"HitFix1\"/> [[John Hurt]] played Abraham Setrakian in the original version of the pilot, but later dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/11/fxs-the-strain-gets-official-13-episode-order/|title=FX's 'The Strain' Gets Official 13-Episode Order, Abraham Role To Be Recast|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|publisher=Deadline.com|date=November 19, 2013|accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref> The role was recast with [[David Bradley (English actor)|David Bradley]] and his scenes were reshot with Bradley.<ref name=\"bradley\"/> Del Toro had previously expressed interest in casting [[Roy Dotrice]], who played Setrakian in several live-action advertisements for the first novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IQ3i35X44DI|title=Guillermo del Toro and Chuck Hogan \u2013 The Fall|author=WGBHForum|publisher=YouTube|time=30:40|quote=If you see the trailers we did for the first book, I would love... some of the casting ideas were there. Roy Dotrice. I would love Roy Dotrice to play Setrakian, you know. He's a fantastic actor. And to have Roy Dotrice and Ron Perlman again after ''Beauty and the Beast'' \u2013 it would be a geek dream.|date=September 6, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref> [[Kevin Durand]], who appeared in Cuse's previous show ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'', was cast as Vasiliy Fet, although the character was originally created with regular del Toro collaborator [[Ron Perlman]] in mind.<ref name=\"HitFix1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cinemaknifefight.com/2010/09/28/a-night-with-guillermo-del-toro-and-chuck-hogan/|title=A Night with GUILLERMO DEL TORO and CHUCK HOGAN|publisher=Cinema Knife Fight|date=September 23, 2010|accessdate=April 27, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305182702/http://balzertown.com/cinemaknifefight/2010/09/28/a-night-with-guillermo-del-toro-and-chuck-hogan/|archivedate=March 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Lauren Lee Smith]] was originally cast as Kelly Goodweather, but was ultimately replaced by [[Natalie Brown (actress)|Natalie Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/06/fx-pilot-castings-lauren-lee-smith-in-the-strain-brett-gelman-jenny-slate-in-gurland/|title=FX Pilot Castings: Lauren Lee Smith In 'The Strain'; Brett Gelman, Jenny Slate In Gurland|publisher=Deadline.com|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref> Del Toro wanted [[Doug Jones (actor)|Doug Jones]] for a major role, but the actor had to decline because of scheduling conflicts; he later played the Ancient and the Master's previous incarnation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/new/exclusive-qa-doug-jones-talks-the-strain-crimson-peak-falling-skies-and-more/|title=Exclusive Q&A: Doug Jones talks \"THE STRAIN\", \"CRIMSON PEAK\", \"FALLING SKIES\" and more\u2026|last=Hanley|first=Ken W.|work=[[Fangoria]]|date=July 9, 2015|accessdate=July 15, 2015}}</ref> [[Sean Astin]] was cast as Jim Kent because del Toro and Cuse \"thought it would be funny to have the most famous sidekick of all times be a betrayer\".<ref name=\"HitFix1\"/> For the second season, [[Max Charles]] replaced Ben Hyland in the series regular role of Zach Goodweather.<ref name=\"zach recast\"/>\n\n=== Filming ===\nThe pilot episode began principal photography on September 17, 2013, in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1710026/guillermo-del-toro-emma-watson-beauty-beast/|title=Finding Emma Watson's Beastly Costar Tops Guillermo Del Toro's To-Do List|last=Sullivan|first=Kevin P.|publisher=MTV|date=July 3, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2013/05/29/new-premium-series-added-to-fx-canadas-lineup/|title=New premium series added to FX Canada's lineup|publisher=CityNews|date=May 29, 2013|accessdate=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Shooting of the pilot was finished on October 31, 2013. FX ordered 13 episodes. Season one was expected to film from November 25, 2013, to April 30, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iatse873.com/current_productions|title=Current Productions|publisher=IATSE 873|accessdate=November 23, 2013}}</ref> A full writing staff was hired to script subsequent episodes. FX reportedly committed $500,000 to creature creation.<ref name=\"Stoll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/04/corey-stoll-to-star-in-the-strain-guillermo-del-toro-series-fx/|title=Corey Stoll To Topline FX's 'The Strain', From Guillermo Del Toro & Carlton Cuse|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|publisher=Deadline.com|date=April 25, 2013|accessdate=April 27, 2013}}</ref> Twelve swords used in the series were provided by [[Missoula, Montana]]-based bladesmith company Zombie Tools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ravallirepublic.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/article_76d7e4e0-78e6-53d0-aa01-2b70e7b8d9bc.html|title=Zombie Tools swords to be used in new Guillermo del Toro series|last=Kato|first=Dillon|work=Ravalli Republic|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=July 1, 2014}}</ref> Production began for the second season in Toronto in November 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/1495307/toronto-shot-the-strain-renewed-for-a-second-season/ |title=Toronto-shot 'The Strain' renewed for a second season |publisher=Global News |first=John R. |last=Kennedy |date=August 6, 2014 |accessdate=August 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n[[File:Ramin Djawadi.jpg|thumb|right|alt=Ramin Djawadi|upright|[[Ramin Djawadi]] is the composer of ''The Strain'' score.]]\nThe music was composed by [[Ramin Djawadi]], who previously scored del Toro's 2013 film ''[[Pacific Rim (film)|Pacific Rim]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2013/09/27/ramin-djawadi-to-score-guillermo-del-toros-the-strain/|title=Ramin Djawadi to Score Guillermo Del Toro's ''The Strain''|publisher=Film Music Reporter|date=September 27, 2013|accessdate=October 2, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Marketing ===\nThe original key art for the series prominently featured a worm, a vector of the vampiric virus, burrowing into a person's eye. Following complaints from members of the public, FX announced that they would replace the artwork on several of their billboards.<ref name=\"poster\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2014/06/27/fx-the-strain-gross-billboards/|title=FX yanks gross billboards for ''The Strain''|last=Rice|first=Lynette|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 27, 2014|accessdate=July 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Main|List of The Strain episodes}}\n{{:List of The Strain episodes}}\n\n== Reception ==\nThe first season received generally positive reviews from critics and has a [[Metacritic]] rating of 72 out of 100 based on 38 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-strain/season-1 |title=The Strain \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref> On [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season holds an 87% \"Certified Fresh\" rating with an average score of 7.6 out of 10 based on 55 reviews. Its consensus states \"''The Strain'' makes the most of its familiar themes through an effective mix of supernatural thrills and B-movie gore \u2013 though it may not appeal to everyone\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-strain/s01/ |title=The Strain: Season 1 (2014) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=September 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second season received generally positive reviews and has a Metacritic rating of 66 out of 100 based on 8 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-strain/season-2 |title=The Strain \u2013 Season 2 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, the season has a rating of 79% with an average score of 7.2 out of 10 based on 19 reviews.  Its consensus states \"The Strain's gory action helps compensate for an unfocused narrative, while the show's political and philosophical subtext add necessary heft for adult viewers.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-strain/s02/ |title=The Strain: Season 2 (2015) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received generally positive reviews and has a Metacritic rating of 62 out of 100 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/the-strain/season-3 |title=The Strain \u2013 Season 3 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=August 29, 2016}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, the season has a rating of 57% with an average score of 6.1 out of 10 based on 7 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-strain/s03/ |title=The Strain: Season 3 (2016) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received generally positive reviews. On Rotten Tomatoes, the season has a rating of 100% with an average score of 7.65 out of 10 based on 7 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/the-strain/s04/ |title=The Strain: Season 4 (2017) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and nominations ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Nominee !! Result !! {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2014 || [[Critics' Choice Television Award|Critics Choice Television Awards]] || Most Exciting New Series || ''The Strain'' || {{won}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=2014 // Winners and Nominees from the 4th Annual Critics' Choice Television Awards|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/television-awards/2014-winners-from-the-4th-annual-critics-choice-television-awards/|publisher=Critics' Choice Awards|date=June 1, 2015|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards]] || Best Genre Television Series || ''The Strain'' || {{nom}} || <ref>{{cite web|title=2014 {{!}} Categories {{!}} International Press Academy|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/award_cat/2014/|publisher=International Press Academy|accessdate=April 9, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=6| 2015 || rowspan=3| [[41st Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]] || Best Syndicated/Cable Television Series || ''The Strain'' |